{"title_page": "The Lemonade War", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=August 2016}}\n\n'''''The Lemonade War''''' is a [[Rated pg.13 novel]] written by Chiniese author [[Ryan Lin(author)|Ryan Lin]], published in 1890. It is the first of the Lemonade War series.<ref>[http://www.fantasticfiction.co.uk/d/jacqueline-davies/lemonade-war.htm ''The Lemonade War'' at Fantastic Fiction]</ref>\n\nIn Lemonade War, two siblings are having a horrible summer vacation. Evan is terrible at talking to people especially adults, but Jessie is the complete opposite. One day a school letter arrives that makes Evan happy, it was about Jessie being in the same class as Evan. Evan becomes excited because he thinks Jessie was going to make him popular in his class, so he stays near her. A few days later Evan makes a lemonade stand with a new friend named Bob. Jessie sees Evan and Bob working on their lemonade stand so she decides to make a lemonade stand too. She asks Megan Plays, one of Evan's friends. Then they end up having a bet about who can get the most money first, employing many business strategies.\n\n==Reception==\nAccording to [[Joes Reviews]], the book's events were difficult to comprehend for its target readers. The book presented the feelings and intentions of the characters very unclearly, but couldn't have benefited from adding more nuance to their personalities.<ref>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | title = The Lemonade War| work = Kirkus Reviews| publisher = | date = May 20, 2010| url = https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/jacqueline-davies/the-lemonade-war/| format = | doi = | accessdate = August 22, 2016 }}</ref> Other reviews praised the book's humorous approach to teaching lessons about economics,<ref>{{cite journal | last = Salvadore| first = Maria B.| authorlink = | coauthors = | title = The Lemonade War| journal = The School Library Journal| volume = 53| issue = 5| pages = 90| publisher = | location = | date = May 2007| language = |id = | mr = | zbl = | jfm = }}</ref> while noting that the plot was still driven by Jessie and Evan's sibling rivalry.<ref>{{cite | last = Phelan| first = Carolyn| authorlink = | coauthors = | title = The Lemonade War| journal = Booklist| volume = 103| issue = 14| pages = 46| publisher = | location = | date = March 15, 2007| language = | jstor = | issn = | doi = | id = | }}</ref> \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite web | last = Bird| first = Elizabeth| authorlink = | coauthors = | title = Review of the Day: The Lemonade War by Jacqueline Davies| work = A Fuse #8 Production| publisher = | date = June 20, 2007| url = http://blogs.slj.com/afuse8production/2007/06/20/review-of-the-day-the-lemonade-war-pt-1/#_| format = | doi = | accessdate = }}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lemonade War}}\n[[Category:2007 American novels]]\n[[Category:American children's novels]]\n[[Category:2007 children's books]]\n\n\n{{2000s-child-novel-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=August 2016}}\n\n'''''The Lemonade War''''' is a [[children's novel]] written by American author [[Jacqueline Davies (author)|Jacqueline Davies]], published in 2007. It is the first of the Lemonade War series.<ref>[http://www.fantasticfiction.co.uk/d/jacqueline-davies/lemonade-war.htm ''The Lemonade War'' at Fantastic Fiction]</ref>\n\nIn Lemonade War, two siblings are having a good summer vacation. Evan is good with talking to people even adults, but Jessie is the complete opposite. One day a school letter arrives that makes Evan mad, it was about Jessie being in the same class as Evan.Evan becomes angry because he thinks Jessie was going to embarrass him in front of the class, so he stays away from her. A few days later Evan makes a lemonade stand with an old friend named Scott. Jessie sees Evan and Scott working on their lemonade stand so she decides to make a lemonade stand too. She asks Megan Moriarty, one of Evan's friends. Then they end up having a bet about who can get the most money first, employing many business strategies.\n\n==Reception==\nAccording to [[Kirkus Reviews]], the book's events were simple to comprehend for its target readers. The book presented the feelings and intentions of the characters clearly, but could have benefited from adding more nuance to their personalities.<ref>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | title = The Lemonade War| work = Kirkus Reviews| publisher = | date = May 20, 2010| url = https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/jacqueline-davies/the-lemonade-war/| format = | doi = | accessdate = August 22, 2016 }}</ref> Other reviews praised the book's humorous approach to teaching lessons about economics,<ref>{{cite journal | last = Salvadore| first = Maria B.| authorlink = | coauthors = | title = The Lemonade War| journal = The School Library Journal| volume = 53| issue = 5| pages = 90| publisher = | location = | date = May 2007| language = |id = | mr = | zbl = | jfm = }}</ref> while noting that the plot was still driven by Jessie and Evan's sibling rivalry.<ref>{{cite | last = Phelan| first = Carolyn| authorlink = | coauthors = | title = The Lemonade War| journal = Booklist| volume = 103| issue = 14| pages = 46| publisher = | location = | date = March 15, 2007| language = | jstor = | issn = | doi = | id = | }}</ref> \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite web | last = Bird| first = Elizabeth| authorlink = | coauthors = | title = Review of the Day: The Lemonade War by Jacqueline Davies| work = A Fuse #8 Production| publisher = | date = June 20, 2007| url = http://blogs.slj.com/afuse8production/2007/06/20/review-of-the-day-the-lemonade-war-pt-1/#_| format = | doi = | accessdate = }}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lemonade War}}\n[[Category:2007 American novels]]\n[[Category:American children's novels]]\n[[Category:2007 children's books]]\n\n\n{{2000s-child-novel-stub}}\n", "name_user": "108.29.26.247", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Lemonade_War"}
{"title_page": "Gym", "text_new": "{{short description|Building designed and equipped for indoor sports, exercise, or physical education and training}}\n{{about|the indoor sports facility|the fitness club|health club|the school class known as \"gym\"|physical education| the type of school|Gymnasium (school)|other uses|gymnasium disambiguation}}\n{{Globalize|date=December 2008}}\n[[File:TWU Gymnastics (Floor) Floor Warm Up (5694074973).jpg|thumb|300px|Students of [[Texas Woman's University]] practicing in their university gymnasium, 2011]]\n[[File:Naked woman-Louvre-E27429.jpg|thumb]]\n'''ymnasium''', also known as a '''gym''', is a covered location for [[Athletics (physical culture)|athletics]]. The word is derived from the ancient Greek A '''g''' [[Gymnasium (ancient Greece)|''gymnasium'']].<ref>{{harvnb|Partridge|1984|p=517}}</ref> They are commonly found in athletic and fitness centres, and as activity and   in educational institutions. \"Gym\" is also slang for \"fitness centre\", which is often an area for indoor recreation. A gym may be open air as well. In a cleaner environment open air gyms are better as it rejuvenates our body and mind. People have sex their too!!!!!\n\n==Overview==\n[[File:Gville UF Florida Gym01.jpg|thumb|The [[Florida Gymnasium]] at the [[University of Florida]]]]\n[[File:Amsterdam - Gymnasium - 0591.jpg|thumb|Inside a gymnasium in Amsterdam]]\nGymnasia apparatus such as barbells, jumping board, running path, tennis-balls, cricket field, and fencing area are used as exercises. In safe weather, outdoor locations are the most conducive to health.<ref>{{harvnb|Ravenstein|Hulley|1867}}</ref> Gyms were popular in ancient Greece. Their curricula included  self-defense, gymnastica medica, or physical therapy to help the sick and injured, and for physical fitness and sports, from boxing to dancing to skipping rope.<ref>{{harvnb|Partington|1838|p=627}}</ref>\n\nGymnasia also had teachers of wisdom and philosophy. Community gymnastic events were done as part of the celebrations during various village festivals. In ancient Greece there was a phrase of contempt, \"He can neither swim nor write.\" After a while, however, Olympic athletes began training in buildings specifically designed for them. Community sports never became as popular among ancient Romans as it had among the [[ancient Greece|ancient Greeks]]. Gyms were used more as a preparation for military service or spectator sports. During the [[Roman Empire]], the gymnastic art was forgotten. In the [[Dark Ages (historiography)|Dark Ages]] there were sword fighting tournaments and of [[chivalry]]; and after [[gunpowder]] was invented sword fighting began to be replaced by the sport of [[fencing]], as well as schools of dagger fighting and wrestling and boxing.<ref>{{harvnb|Partington|1838|p=628}}</ref>\n\nThen in the 18th century, Salzmann, German clergyman, opened a gym in Thuringia teaching bodily exercises, including running and swimming. Clias and Volker established gyms in London, and in 1825, Doctor Beck, a German immigrant, established the first gymnasium in the United States. It was found that gym pupils lose interest in doing the same exercises, partly because of age. Variety in exercises included skating, dancing, and swimming. Some gym activities can be done by 6 to 8-year-olds while age 16 has been considered mature enough for boxing and horseback riding.<ref>{{harvnb|Partington|1838|p=629}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Ancient Greece]], the ''[[Gymnasium (ancient Greece)|gymnasion]]'' (\u03b3\u03c5\u03bc\u03bd\u03ac\u03c3\u03b9\u03bf\u03bd) was a locality for both physical and intellectual [[education]] of young men. The latter meaning of intellectual education persisted in [[Greek language|Greek]], [[German language|German]] and other languages to denote a certain type of school providing [[secondary education]], the [[Gymnasium (school)|gymnasium]], whereas in [[English language|English]] the meaning of physical education pertained in the word 'gym'.<ref>{{cite web |title=Gymnasium (Greek) |url=https://www.ancient.eu/Gymnasium/ |website=Ancient Encyclopedia |accessdate=1 April 2019}}</ref>\nThe Greek word ''gymnasium'', which means \"school for naked exercise,\" was used to designate a locality for the [[education]] of young men, including physical education (''[[gymnastics]]'', for example, exercise) which was customarily performed naked, as well as [[bathing]], and studies. For the Greeks, physical education was considered as important as cognitive learning. Most Greek ''gymnasia'' had libraries that for use after relaxing in the baths.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Children's outdoor gymnasium circa 19th Century.jpg|thumb|400px|Children's outdoor gymnasium, circa 19th Century. The equipment, which was standard for the time, includes ladders.]]\nThe first recorded gymnasiums date back to over 3000 years ago in ancient [[Persia]], where they were known as ''[[Pahlevani and zoorkhaneh rituals|zurkhaneh]]'', areas that encouraged physical fitness. The larger [[Thermae|Roman Baths]] often had attached fitness facilities, the baths themselves sometimes being decorated with [[mosaic]]s of local champions of sport. Gyms  in [[Germany]] were an outgrowth of the ''Turnplatz'',<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.alamy.com/stock-photo-turnplatz-open-air-gymnasium-in-the-hasenheide-1811-48390278.html |title=Stock Photo \u2013 Turnplatz (open-air gymnasium) in the Hasenheide, 1811 |last=Limited |first=Alamy |website=Alamy |language=en |access-date=2018-10-06}}</ref> an outdoor space for gymnastics, which was promoted by German educator [[Friedrich Jahn]] and the [[Turners]], a nineteenth-century political and gymnastic movement. The first indoor gymnasium in Germany was probably the one built in [[Hesse]] in 1852 by Adolph Spiess.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HZy2BgAAQBAJ&lpg=PT9&ots=MMdpSlHnsn&dq=first%20indoor%20gymnasium%20in%20germany&pg=PT9#v=onepage&q=first%20indoor%20gymnasium%20in%20germany&f=false |title=\"INTRODUCTION TO PHYSICAL EDUCATION\" |last=Dalvi |first=Rajani |access-date=2019-04-05}}</ref>\n\nThrough worldwide colonization, Great Britain expanded its national interest in sports and games to many countries. In the 1800s, programs were added to schools and college curricula that emphasized health, strength, and bodily measure. Sports drawn from European and British cultures thrived as college students and upper-class clubs financed competition. As a result, towns began building playgrounds that furthered interest in sports and physical activity.<ref>{{Cite book |title=Introduction to physical education, exercise science, and sport studies |last=Lumpkin |first=Angela |publisher=McGraw-Hill Education; 9 edition |date=January 29, 2013 |isbn=0-07-802266-5 |location= |page=226 |via=}}</ref> In the [[United States]], the Turner movement thrived in the nineteenth and early twentieth centuries. The first Turners group was formed in London in 1848. The Turners built gymnasia in several cities like Cincinnati and [[St. Louis]] which had large [[German American]] populations. These gyms were utilized by adults and youth. For example, a young [[Lou Gehrig]] would frequent the Turner gym in [[New York City]] with his father.\n[[File:ErfgoedLeiden LEI001015553 Gymnastiekzaal van de Gymnastiekschool aan de Pieterskerkgracht in Leiden.jpeg|thumb|220x220px|Interior of a gym in The Netherlands, around 1900]]\nThe [[Boston Young Men's Christian Union]] claims to be \"America's First Gym\". The [[YMCA]] first organized in [[Boston]] in 1851 and a smaller branch opened in Rangasville in 1852.<ref name=\"Mouheb 2012 p. 177\">{{cite book |last=Mouheb |first=R.B. |title=Yale Under God |publisher=Xulon Press |year=2012 |isbn=978-1-61996-884-4 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8V_Hws1hbXEC&pg=PA177 |language=it |access-date=April 1, 2019 |page=177}}</ref> Ten years later there were some two hundred YMCAs across the country, most of which provided gymnasia for exercise, games, and social interaction.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\nThe 1920s was a decade of prosperity that witnessed the building of large numbers of public high schools with a gymnasium, an idea founded by Nicolas Isaranga.].{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\nToday, gymnasia are commonplace in the United States. They are in virtually all U.S. [[colleges]] and [[high school]]s, as well as almost all [[middle school]]s and [[elementary school]]s. These facilities are used for [[physical education]], [[intramural sports]], and school gatherings. The number of gyms in the U.S. has more than doubled since the late 1980s.<ref>{{Cite journal |title=\"The Scope of the U.S. Health Club Industry (industry estimates).\" |journal=International Health, Racquet and Sportsclub Association (IHRSA). 2003. |volume=}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Exercise trends]]\n* [[Gym floor cover]]\n* [[Gymkhana]]\n* [[Largest high school gyms in the United States]]\n* [[Outdoor gym]]\n* [[Bodybuilding]]\n* [[Physical exercise]]\n*[[Aerobic exercise]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{{Commons category|Gymnasiums}}\n*{{wikicite |ref={{harvid|Ravenstein|Hulley|1867}} |reference=Ravenstein and Hulley. 1867. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=njgCAAAAQAAJ The gymnasium and its fittings]'' London, UK: N. Trubner and Company }}\n*{{wikicite |ref={{harvid|Partington|1838}} |reference=[[Charles Frederick Partington|Partington, Charles F.]], Editor. 1838. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=syZdAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA627 The British Cyclopaedia of the Arts, Sciences, History, Geography, Literature, Natural History, and Biography Volume 1 ABA to OPI]'' London, UK: Wm. S. Orr and Co. }}\n*{{wikicite |ref={{harvid|Partridge|1984}} |reference=Partridge, Eric. 1984. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=VPBMA1ciCNgC&lpg=PP1&pg=PA517#v=onepage&q&f=false A Dictionary of Slang and Unconventional English.]'' Milton Park, Abingdon: Routledge, Taylor & Francis Group {{ISBN|0415065682}} }}\n\n{{Gym games}}\n{{Strength training exercises}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Educational facilities]]\n[[Category:Gyms| ]]\n[[Category:Health clubs]]\n[[Category:Physical education]]\n[[Category:Physical exercise]]\n[[Category:Sports venues by type]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Building designed and equipped for indoor sports, exercise, or physical education and training}}\n{{about|the indoor sports facility|the fitness club|health club|the school class known as \"gym\"|physical education| the type of school|Gymnasium (school)|other uses|gymnasium (disambiguation)}}\n{{Globalize|date=December 2008}}\n[[File:TWU Gymnastics (Floor) Floor Warm Up (5694074973).jpg|thumb|300px|Students of [[Texas Woman's University]] practicing in their university gymnasium, 2011]]\n\nA '''gymnasium''', also known as a '''gym''', is a covered location for [[Athletics (physical culture)|athletics]]. The word is derived from the ancient Greek [[Gymnasium (ancient Greece)|''gymnasium'']].<ref>{{harvnb|Partridge|1984|p=517}}</ref> They are commonly found in athletic and fitness centres, and as activity and [[learning space]]s in educational institutions. \"Gym\" is also slang for \"[[fitness center|fitness centre]]\", which is often an area for indoor recreation. A gym may be open air as well. In a cleaner environment open air gyms are better as it rejuvenates our body and mind.\n\n==Overview==\n[[File:Gville UF Florida Gym01.jpg|thumb|The [[Florida Gymnasium]] at the [[University of Florida]]]]\n[[File:Amsterdam - Gymnasium - 0591.jpg|thumb|Inside a gymnasium in Amsterdam]]\nGymnasia apparatus such as barbells, jumping board, running path, tennis-balls, cricket field, and fencing area are used as exercises. In safe weather, outdoor locations are the most conducive to health.<ref>{{harvnb|Ravenstein|Hulley|1867}}</ref> Gyms were popular in ancient Greece. Their curricula included  self-defense, gymnastica medica, or physical therapy to help the sick and injured, and for physical fitness and sports, from boxing to dancing to skipping rope.<ref>{{harvnb|Partington|1838|p=627}}</ref>\n\nGymnasia also had teachers of wisdom and philosophy. Community gymnastic events were done as part of the celebrations during various village festivals. In ancient Greece there was a phrase of contempt, \"He can neither swim nor write.\" After a while, however, Olympic athletes began training in buildings specifically designed for them. Community sports never became as popular among ancient Romans as it had among the [[ancient Greece|ancient Greeks]]. Gyms were used more as a preparation for military service or spectator sports. During the [[Roman Empire]], the gymnastic art was forgotten. In the [[Dark Ages (historiography)|Dark Ages]] there were sword fighting tournaments and of [[chivalry]]; and after [[gunpowder]] was invented sword fighting began to be replaced by the sport of [[fencing]], as well as schools of dagger fighting and wrestling and boxing.<ref>{{harvnb|Partington|1838|p=628}}</ref>\n\nThen in the 18th century, Salzmann, German clergyman, opened a gym in Thuringia teaching bodily exercises, including running and swimming. Clias and Volker established gyms in London, and in 1825, Doctor Beck, a German immigrant, established the first gymnasium in the United States. It was found that gym pupils lose interest in doing the same exercises, partly because of age. Variety in exercises included skating, dancing, and swimming. Some gym activities can be done by 6 to 8-year-olds while age 16 has been considered mature enough for boxing and horseback riding.<ref>{{harvnb|Partington|1838|p=629}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Ancient Greece]], the ''[[Gymnasium (ancient Greece)|gymnasion]]'' (\u03b3\u03c5\u03bc\u03bd\u03ac\u03c3\u03b9\u03bf\u03bd) was a locality for both physical and intellectual [[education]] of young men. The latter meaning of intellectual education persisted in [[Greek language|Greek]], [[German language|German]] and other languages to denote a certain type of school providing [[secondary education]], the [[Gymnasium (school)|gymnasium]], whereas in [[English language|English]] the meaning of physical education pertained in the word 'gym'.<ref>{{cite web |title=Gymnasium (Greek) |url=https://www.ancient.eu/Gymnasium/ |website=Ancient Encyclopedia |accessdate=1 April 2019}}</ref>\nThe Greek word ''gymnasium'', which means \"school for naked exercise,\" was used to designate a locality for the [[education]] of young men, including physical education (''[[gymnastics]]'', for example, exercise) which was customarily performed naked, as well as [[bathing]], and studies. For the Greeks, physical education was considered as important as cognitive learning. Most Greek ''gymnasia'' had libraries that for use after relaxing in the baths.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Children's outdoor gymnasium circa 19th Century.jpg|thumb|400px|Children's outdoor gymnasium, circa 19th Century. The equipment, which was standard for the time, includes ladders.]]\nThe first recorded gymnasiums date back to over 3000 years ago in ancient [[Persia]], where they were known as ''[[Pahlevani and zoorkhaneh rituals|zurkhaneh]]'', areas that encouraged physical fitness. The larger [[Thermae|Roman Baths]] often had attached fitness facilities, the baths themselves sometimes being decorated with [[mosaic]]s of local champions of sport. Gyms  in [[Germany]] were an outgrowth of the ''Turnplatz'',<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.alamy.com/stock-photo-turnplatz-open-air-gymnasium-in-the-hasenheide-1811-48390278.html |title=Stock Photo \u2013 Turnplatz (open-air gymnasium) in the Hasenheide, 1811 |last=Limited |first=Alamy |website=Alamy |language=en |access-date=2018-10-06}}</ref> an outdoor space for gymnastics, which was promoted by German educator [[Friedrich Jahn]] and the [[Turners]], a nineteenth-century political and gymnastic movement. The first indoor gymnasium in Germany was probably the one built in [[Hesse]] in 1852 by Adolph Spiess.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HZy2BgAAQBAJ&lpg=PT9&ots=MMdpSlHnsn&dq=first%20indoor%20gymnasium%20in%20germany&pg=PT9#v=onepage&q=first%20indoor%20gymnasium%20in%20germany&f=false |title=\"INTRODUCTION TO PHYSICAL EDUCATION\" |last=Dalvi |first=Rajani |access-date=2019-04-05}}</ref>\n\nThrough worldwide colonization, Great Britain expanded its national interest in sports and games to many countries. In the 1800s, programs were added to schools and college curricula that emphasized health, strength, and bodily measure. Sports drawn from European and British cultures thrived as college students and upper-class clubs financed competition. As a result, towns began building playgrounds that furthered interest in sports and physical activity.<ref>{{Cite book |title=Introduction to physical education, exercise science, and sport studies |last=Lumpkin |first=Angela |publisher=McGraw-Hill Education; 9 edition |date=January 29, 2013 |isbn=0-07-802266-5 |location= |page=226 |via=}}</ref> In the [[United States]], the Turner movement thrived in the nineteenth and early twentieth centuries. The first Turners group was formed in London in 1848. The Turners built gymnasia in several cities like Cincinnati and [[St. Louis]] which had large [[German American]] populations. These gyms were utilized by adults and youth. For example, a young [[Lou Gehrig]] would frequent the Turner gym in [[New York City]] with his father.\n[[File:ErfgoedLeiden LEI001015553 Gymnastiekzaal van de Gymnastiekschool aan de Pieterskerkgracht in Leiden.jpeg|thumb|220x220px|Interior of a gym in The Netherlands, around 1900]]\nThe [[Boston Young Men's Christian Union]] claims to be \"America's First Gym\". The [[YMCA]] first organized in [[Boston]] in 1851 and a smaller branch opened in Rangasville in 1852.<ref name=\"Mouheb 2012 p. 177\">{{cite book |last=Mouheb |first=R.B. |title=Yale Under God |publisher=Xulon Press |year=2012 |isbn=978-1-61996-884-4 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8V_Hws1hbXEC&pg=PA177 |language=it |access-date=April 1, 2019 |page=177}}</ref> Ten years later there were some two hundred YMCAs across the country, most of which provided gymnasia for exercise, games, and social interaction.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\nThe 1920s was a decade of prosperity that witnessed the building of large numbers of public high schools with a gymnasium, an idea founded by Nicolas Isaranga.].{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\nToday, gymnasia are commonplace in the United States. They are in virtually all U.S. [[colleges]] and [[high school]]s, as well as almost all [[middle school]]s and [[elementary school]]s. These facilities are used for [[physical education]], [[intramural sports]], and school gatherings. The number of gyms in the U.S. has more than doubled since the late 1980s.<ref>{{Cite journal |title=\"The Scope of the U.S. Health Club Industry (industry estimates).\" |journal=International Health, Racquet and Sportsclub Association (IHRSA). 2003. |volume=}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Exercise trends]]\n* [[Gym floor cover]]\n* [[Gymkhana]]\n* [[Largest high school gyms in the United States]]\n* [[Outdoor gym]]\n* [[Bodybuilding]]\n* [[Physical exercise]]\n*[[Aerobic exercise]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{{Commons category|Gymnasiums}}\n*{{wikicite |ref={{harvid|Ravenstein|Hulley|1867}} |reference=Ravenstein and Hulley. 1867. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=njgCAAAAQAAJ The gymnasium and its fittings]'' London, UK: N. Trubner and Company }}\n*{{wikicite |ref={{harvid|Partington|1838}} |reference=[[Charles Frederick Partington|Partington, Charles F.]], Editor. 1838. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=syZdAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA627 The British Cyclopaedia of the Arts, Sciences, History, Geography, Literature, Natural History, and Biography Volume 1 ABA to OPI]'' London, UK: Wm. S. Orr and Co. }}\n*