{"title_page": "Jennifer Pan", "text_new": "{{short description|Vietnamese-Canadian convicted of matricide and attempted patricide}}\n{{Infobox criminal\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name = \n| honorific_suffix = \n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| image = JenniferPan.png\n| image_upright = \n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date =   {{birth date and age|1986|6|17|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], [[Canada]]\n| disappeared_date = \n| disappeared_place = \n| disappeared_status = \n| death_date =     <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| body_discovered = \n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates =\n| monuments = \n| residence = \n| nationality = [[Canadian]]\n| other_names = \n| citizenship = Canada\n| education = [[Mary Ward Catholic Secondary School]] (did not graduate)\n| alma_mater = \n| occupation = \n| years_active = \n| employer = \n| organization = \n| agent = \n| known_for = \n| notable_works = \n| style = \n| home_town = \n| salary = \n| net_worth = \n| height = \n| weight = \n| television = \n| title = \n| term = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| party = \n| movement = \n| opponents = \n| boards = \n| religion = \n| denomination = \n| criminal_charge = {{ublist|First-degree murder|Attempted murder|Conspiracy to commit murder}}\n| conviction_penalty = [[Life imprisonment]] with possibility of parole after 25 years\n| conviction_status = Incarcerated\n| spouse =         <!-- Do not include unless notable or relevant to the crime involved -->\n| children =       <!-- (as above) -->\n| parents = {{ublist|Huei Hann Pan|Bich Ha Pan}}\n| relatives = Felix Pan\n| callsign = \n| awards = \n| website = \n| allegiance = \n| motive = Romantic relationship, monetary gain, alleged child abuse\n| conviction = \n| reward_amount = \n| capture_status = \n| wanted_by = \n| partners = \n| wanted_since = \n| time_at_large = \n| escaped = \n| escape_end = \n| comments = \n| victims = Bich Ha Pan\n| date = November 8, 2010\n| time = \n| beginyear = \n| endyear = \n| country = Canada\n| states = \n| locations = \n| targets = \n| fatalities = \n| injuries = \n| weapons = \n| apprehended = \n| imprisoned = \n| module =\n| signature =\n| signature_size =\n| signature_alt = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''Jennifer Pan''' (born 17 June 1986) is a [[Vietnamese Canadians|Vietnamese-Canadian]] woman of [[Chinese people|Chinese]]-[[Vietnamese people|Vietnamese]] ancestry convicted of a 2010 [[Contract killing|kill-for-hire]] attack targeting both of her parents, in response to their allegedly abusive \"[[tiger parenting]]\" into her mid-20s. The crime took place at the Pan residence in [[Unionville, Ontario|Unionville]], [[Markham, Ontario|Markham]], [[Ontario]], in the [[Greater Toronto Area]]. Jeremy Grimaldi, a journalist of the ''[[Markham Economist & Sun]]'' and the author of ''[[A Daughter's Deadly Deception: The Jennifer Pan Story]]'', stated that the affair \"captivated many, if for nothing else than the sheer intrigue of a case involving [[matricide]], a rarity in Canada.\"<ref name=Grimaldi18years>{{cite news|last=Grimaldi|first=Jeremy|url=https://www.yorkregion.com/news-story/6163269-carty-gets-18-years-for-his-part-in-markham-s-pan-murder/|title=Carty gets 18 years for his part in Markham's Pan murder|work=[[Markham Economist & Sun]]|date=December 7, 2015|accessdate=September 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nJennifer Pan's mother Bich Ha (pronounced \"Bick\"){{#tag:ref|''Bich Ha Pan'': {{zh|first=c,j|c=\u6881\u78a7\u971e|j=loeng4 bik1 haa4|p=Li\u00e1ng B\u00ecxi\u00e1}}<ref name=ZHnameparents>Source of Chinese names: {{cite web|url=http://news.singtao.ca/toronto/content_column_tor.php?IndexID=2863523|title=\u300c\u4e56\u4e56\u5973\u300d\u88ab\u63a7\u5f12\u6bcd.\u842c\u9326\u5165\u5c4b\u52ab\u6bba\u6848\u5cf0\u8ff4\u8def\u8f49|work=[[Sing Tao Daily (Canada)|Sing Tao]]|date=November 24, 2010|accessdate=September 18, 2018}}</ref>|group=note}} and father Huei Hann Pan{{#tag:ref|''Huei Hann Pan'': {{zh|first=t,j||t=\u6f58\u6f22\u8f1d|s=\u6f58\u6c49\u8f89|j=pun1 hon3 fai1|p=P\u0101n H\u00e0nhu\u012b}}<ref name=ZHnameparents/>|group=note}} were Sino-Vietnamese ([[Viet Hoa]]) immigrants to Canada.<ref name=LauImmigrantDream>{{cite news|last1=Lau|first1=Joyce|title=A murder in Toronto and the dark side of the Asian immigrant dream (book review)|url=http://www.scmp.com/magazines/post-magazine/books/article/2043688/murder-toronto-and-dark-side-asian-immigrant-dream|accessdate=9 January 2017|newspaper=[[South China Morning Post]]|date=8 November 2016}}</ref> Hann was born and educated in [[Vietnam]], moving to Canada in 1979 as a [[political refugee]]. Bich also immigrated as a refugee. The couple were married in [[Toronto]] and lived in [[Scarborough, Toronto|Scarborough]]. Their two children are Jennifer, born 1986, and Felix, born 1989.<ref name=\"Revenge\">{{cite magazine|last1=Ho|first1=Karen K.|date=22 July 2015|title=Jennifer Pan's Revenge: The inside story of a golden child, the killers she hired, and the parents she wanted dead|url=http://torontolife.com/city/crime/jennifer-pan-revenge/|magazine=[[Toronto Life]]|accessdate=9 January 2017}} - [https://torontolife.com/city/jennifer-pan-revenge-simplified-chinese-translation/ Version in Simplified Chinese]<!--Old URL: http://web.archive.org/web/20150722213215/http://www.torontolife.com/informer/features/2015/07/22/jennifer-pan-revenge-simplified-chinese-translation/--></ref><ref name=WangGoldenDaughter>{{cite news|last1=Wang|first1=Yanan|title=Tragedy of 'golden' daughter's fall resonates with Asian immigrant children|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2015/07/27/tragedy-of-golden-daughters-murder-plot-against-parents-resonates-with-asian-immigrant-children/|accessdate=9 January 2017|newspaper=[[Washington Post]]|date=27 July 2015}}</ref> The Pans found work at [[Magna International]], an auto parts manufacturer in [[Aurora, Ontario|Aurora]], [[Ontario]].<ref name=Revenge/> Hann worked as a tool and die maker, while Bich made car parts. The couple persistently worked hard for their money to ensure that their children had the upbringing and opportunities they themselves had missed out on. Hann and Bich were thrifty and by 2004 were financially stable enough to purchase a \"large\" house with a two-car garage on a residential street in [[Markham, Ontario|Markham]], a town with a large Asian population.<ref name=LauImmigrantDream/> Bich drove a [[Lexus ES 300]] and Hann drove a [[Mercedes-Benz C-Class (W203)]]. They had accumulated [[Canadian dollar|CAD$]]200,000 in savings.<ref name=Revenge/>\n\nJennifer's parents set many goals for their children and had extremely high expectations of them. Jennifer was made to take piano lessons at the age of four, as well as [[figure skating]] classes where she trained most days during the week. She had hopes of becoming an [[Olympic Games|Olympic]] figure skating champion until she tore a ligament in her knee. Jennifer attended [[Mary Ward Catholic Secondary School]] where she played the [[flute]] in the school band.<ref name=Revenge/> According to her high school friend Karen K. Ho, Hann was seen as \"the classic [[tiger parenting|tiger dad]],\" and Bich was \"his reluctant accomplice.\" The Pans picked Jennifer up when classes ended each day and monitored her extracurricular activities very closely. They never permitted her to date boys while attending high school, or to attend high school dances or [[prom]]s out of fear that these activities would distract her from her academic commitments. Jennifer was not permitted to attend any parties while her parents believed that she was attending university. At the age of 22, \"she had never gone to a club, been drunk, visited a friend's cottage or gone on vacation without her family.\"<ref name=Revenge/> Jennifer and her friends reportedly regarded this upbringing as restrictive and greatly oppressive.<ref name=Revenge/>\n\nDespite her parents' high expectations and the fact that Jennifer had received good grades in lower school, throughout high school her grades were somewhat average (in the 70% range) except for music. Multiple times, she forged [[report card]]s using false templates to show her parents that she had received straight As when she had not. When Jennifer failed calculus class in her senior year of high school, [[Ryerson University]] rescinded her early admission. As she could not bear to be perceived as a failure, she began to lie to those she knew, including her parents, and pretended she was attending university. Instead, she sat in caf\u00e9s, taught as a piano instructor and worked in a restaurant to earn money. In order to maintain the charade, Jennifer told her parents she had won scholarships, later falsely claiming that she had accepted an offer into the pharmacology program at the [[University of Toronto]]. She went to the extent of purchasing second-hand textbooks and watching videos related to pharmacology in order to create notebooks full of purported class notes that she could show her parents. Jennifer also requested permission from her parents to stay near the campus with a friend throughout the week.<ref name=Revenge/>\n\nJennifer was actually staying with her boyfriend,<ref name=Revenge/> Daniel Chi-Kwong Wong,{{#tag:ref|''Daniel Chi-Kwong Wong'': {{zh|first=t,j|t=\u9ec3\u5fd7\u5149|s=\u9ec4\u5fd7\u5149|j=wong4 zi3 gwong1|p=Hu\u00e1ng Zh\u00ecgu\u0101ng|labels=no}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.singtao.ca/toronto/2014-05-10/city1399706077d5044769.html|title=\u7537\u53cb\u7206\u6f58\u5973\u66fe\u906d5\u6f22\u6027\u4fb5 \u8072\u7a31\u6536\u8b66\u544a\u77ed\u8a0a \u77e2\u53e3\u5426\u8a8d\u6d89\u6848|work=[[Sing Tao Daily]]|date=2014-05-10|accessdate=2018-09-18}}</ref>|group=note}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/4th-arrest-in-markham-home-invasion-homicide-1.1038532|agency=[[The Canadian Press]]|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]]|title=4th arrest in Markham home invasion homicide|date=2011-04-26|accessdate=2018-09-18}}</ref> a high school sweetheart whom her parents knew nothing about.<ref name=Revenge/><ref name=\"BrownChineseCubs\">{{cite news|last1=Brown|first1=Vanessa|title=When Chinese cubs turn on their Tiger Parents|url=http://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/real-life/true-stories/when-chinese-cubs-turn-on-their-tiger-parents/news-story/36ad884522b2d22ba1e2f88faa5d72ab|accessdate=9 January 2017|work=News.com.au|date=11 December 2016}}</ref><ref>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735269}}, 9781459735262, [[Google Books]] [https://books.google.com/books?id=zomGCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT31 PT 31]: \"[...]commenting on the fact that he was only half Chinese. \"[...]you're [part] Filipino.\"\"</ref> Wong was of mixed Chinese and [[Filipino people|Filipino]] ancestry,<ref name=\"BrownChineseCubs\">{{cite news|last1=Brown|first1=Vanessa|title=When Chinese cubs turn on their Tiger Parents|url=http://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/real-life/true-stories/when-chinese-cubs-turn-on-their-tiger-parents/news-story/36ad884522b2d22ba1e2f88faa5d72ab|accessdate=9 January 2017|work=News.com.au|date=11 December 2016}}</ref><ref>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735269}}, 9781459735262, [[Google Books]] [https://books.google.es/books?id=zomGCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT31 PT 31]: \"[...]commenting on the fact that he was only half Chinese. \"[...]you're [part] Filipino.\"\"</ref> resided in [[Ajax, Ontario|Ajax]],<ref name=GillisWendyFifth>{{cite news|author=Gillis, Wendy|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/crime/2011/05/04/fifth_suspect_arrested_in_deadly_markham_home_invasion.html|title=Fifth suspect arrested in deadly Markham home invasion |newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|date=May 4, 2011|accessdate=September 18, 2018}}</ref> and worked at a [[Boston Pizza]] restaurant.<ref name=GrimaldiPT90>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735269}}, 9781459735262, [https://books.google.cz/books?id=zomGCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT90 PT 90]. \"Daniel Wong is arrested at work in front of his colleagues at Boston Pizza on April 26, 2011.\"</ref> Wong, once a student at Mary Ward, transferred to [[Cardinal Carter Academy]] in North York, Toronto due to low grades<!--\"he was falling behind\"-->, and later studied at [[York University]].<ref name=Revenge/> He was an active [[marijuana]] dealer.<ref name=Revenge/><!--\"he had been charged with trafficking after cops found half a pound of weed in his car.\"--><ref name=Dimannoastonishing>{{cite news|last=Dimanno|first=Rosie|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/crime/2014/09/15/the_fantastic_testimony_of_jennifer_pan.html|title=The astonishing testimony of Jennifer Pan|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|date=September 15, 2014|accessdate=September 25, 2018|quote=Seven years until Wong \u2014 Pan says he was the one who put her in touch with \u201cHomeboy,\u201d a man he knew through his marijuana dealing}}</ref>\n\n==Adult life==\nWhile pretending to complete her degree at the University of Toronto, Jennifer told her parents that she had started working as a volunteer at Toronto's [[The Hospital for Sick Children, Toronto|Hospital for Sick Children]], known as Sick Kids. Hann and Bich soon became suspicious when they realized she did not have a hospital ID badge or uniform. On one occasion, Bich followed her daughter to \"work\" and quickly discovered her deception. In a state of shock, Hann wanted to throw Jennifer out of the house, but her mother persuaded him to allow her to stay. As she had not completed high school due to failing calculus, she eventually began working to finish high school completely and was later encouraged by her parents to apply to university. She was, however, forbidden to contact Wong or to go anywhere except to her piano-teaching job. Nevertheless, she and Wong spoke clandestinely during this period.<ref name=Revenge/>\n\nBy the time that Jennifer was 24, Wong had grown weary of trying to pursue a relationship with Jennifer. As she was so daunted and restricted by her parents that she lived at home and only met him in secret, Wong began to date another young woman whom he soon fell in love with.<ref name=Revenge/> Jennifer quickly invented a new story and told Wong that a man had entered her house, showing what appeared to be a police badge. She then told him that several men had rushed in and [[gang rape]]d her. After this, Jennifer insisted that a bullet was mailed to her, telling Wong that it was sent from his new girlfriend.<ref name=Revenge/>\n\n==Murder==\nIn Spring 2010, Jennifer was in contact with Andrew Montemayor, a high school friend who, she claims, had boasted in their high school years about robbing people at knife point, an assertion denied by Montemayor. Montemayor introduced her to Ricardo Duncan, a \"[[Goth subculture|goth]] kid\" whom Pan gave $1,500 to [[contract killing|kill her father]] in the parking lot at his workplace. Duncan says that she once gave him $200 for a night out, but that he returned it, and that he rebuffed her when she asked him to kill her parents.<ref name=Revenge/>\n\nJennifer and Wong were back in contact at this time and according to the police, came up with a plan to hire a professional [[hitman]] for $10,000 to kill her parents, calculating that she would then inherit $500,000. They planned to move in together. Wong connected Pan with a man,<ref name=Revenge/> Lenford Roy Crawford,<ref name=GillisWendyFifth/> Jamaican-born,<ref>Grimaldi, ''[[A Daughter's Deadly Deception]]'', {{ISBN|1459735250}}, 9781459735255, p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=fHlODQAAQBAJ&pg=PA81 81].</ref> whom he called \"Homeboy\", and gave her a [[SIM card]] and an [[iPhone]] so that she could contact Crawford without using her usual cell phone.<ref name=Revenge/> Crawford contacted another man,<ref name=HashamCrownfinishpres>{{cite news|last=Hasham|first=Alyshah|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/crime/2014/08/13/crown_finishes_presenting_evidence_against_jennifer_pan_in_murder_trial.html|title=Crown finishes presenting evidence against Jennifer Pan in murder trial|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|date=August 13, 2014|accessdate=September 20, 2018|quote=[...]who in turn involved David Mylvaganam, allegedly one of three men who[...]It remains unclear who the other two men who entered the house are. The jury has heard that Crawford and Wong were both at work at the time of the murder. }}</ref> named Eric Shawn \"Sniper\" Carty,<ref name=GrimaldiCartydead>{{cite web|last=Grimaldi|first=Jeremy|url=https://www.yorkregion.com/news-story/8680927-eric-carty-linchpin-in-jennifer-pan-murder-plot-dies-in-jail/|title=Eric Carty, linchpin in Jennifer Pan murder plot, dies in jail|work=[[Markham Economist & Sun]]|date=2018-06-26|accessdate=2018-09-29}}</ref> who in turn contacted [[Montreal]]-born David Mylvaganam.<ref name=HashamCrownfinishpres/><ref name=\"LauImmigrantDream\" /> Crawford lived in [[Brampton, Ontario|Brampton]] and Mylvaganam lived in Toronto, while Carty,<ref name=GillisWendyFifth/> who previously lived in [[Rexdale, Toronto]],<ref name=GrimaldiCartydead/> at the time did not have a fixed residence.<ref name=GillisWendyFifth/> The [[The Crown|Crown]] stated that Mylvaganam was one of the hitmen.<ref name=HashamCrownfinishpres/> Carty was later found responsible for an unrelated murder, and Grimaldi stated that Carty was \"a repeat violent offender\".<ref name=Grimaldi18years/>\n\nThe murder took place at the Pan residence in [[Unionville, Ontario|Unionville]], in Markham.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.guelphmercury.com/news-story/4431797-markham-murder-trial-resumes-with-father-still-on-stand/|title=Markham murder trial resumes with father still on stand|agency=[[Markham Economist & Sun]]|work=[[Guelph Mercury Tribune]]|date=March 26, 2014|accessdate=September 19, 2018|quote=[...]in Unionville in this file photograph. This was the scene of the murder of Bich Pan in 2010.}}</ref> On November 8, 2010, Jennifer unlocked the front door of the family home when she went to bed, then spoke by phone to Mylvaganam. Shortly afterwards, Mylvaganam and two other people [[home invasion|entered the home]] through the unlocked front door, all carrying guns.<ref name=Revenge/> In court testimony, the Crown did not establish the identity of the other two hitmen; Wong and Crawford were at work.<ref name=HashamCrownfinishpres/> Carty stated that he was the driver for those who broke into the house, and that he selected them and was involved in plotting the attack. He did not state that he was one of the three or that he directly attacked others.<ref name=Grimaldi18years/> Grimaldi stated that the identity of the triggerperson remains unknown.<ref name=Grimaldi18years/><!--\"To this day, it remains unclear who pulled the trigger,[...]\"-->\n\nAfter demanding all the money in the house and ransacking the main bedroom, the three men took Bich and Hann to the basement where they shot them multiple times. Bich was killed but Hann would survive his wounds. The three men then took all the cash that was in the house, including $2,000 from Jennifer, and left. Jennifer claimed that they tied her up, but that she managed to free her hands and dial [[9-1-1]].<ref name=Revenge/> Hann was treated at [[Markham Stouffville Hospital]],<ref name=Grimaldip17alone>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735250}}, 9781459735255 p. [https://books.google.cz/books?id=fHlODQAAQBAJ&pg=PA17 17].</ref> before being moved to a trauma unit<ref name=Grimaldip27alone>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735250}}, 9781459735255 p. [https://books.google.cz/books?id=fHlODQAAQBAJ&pg=PA27 27].</ref> at [[Sunnybrook Hospital]] in Toronto by aircraft.<ref name=Grimaldip35alone>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735250}}, 9781459735255 p. [https://books.google.cz/books?id=fHlODQAAQBAJ&pg=PA35 35].</ref><ref name=Grimaldip27alone/>\n\n== Investigation and arrests ==\nThe evening after the murder, Jennifer underwent her first interview with the police.<ref name=Grimaldip18alone>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735250}}, 9781459735255 p. [https://books.google.cz/books?id=fHlODQAAQBAJ&pg=PA18 18].</ref> She was arrested on November 22, 2010<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/jennifer-pan-plotted-to-have-parents-killed-says-crown-1.2579135|title=Jennifer Pan plotted to have parents killed, says Crown|agency=[[The Canadian Press]]|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]]|date=March 19, 2014|accessdate=September 18, 2018}}</ref> during her third interview at the Markham police station (5 District) of [[York Regional Police]].<ref name=Grimaldiinterviewarrest>Grimaldi - Interview date: {{ISBN|1459735250}}, 9781459735255 p. [https://books.google.cz/books?id=fHlODQAAQBAJ&pg=PA66 66]. \"During her third police interview, on November 22, 2016, Jennifer opens up to Detective Goetz[...]\" - Arrest: {{ISBN|1459735250}}, 9781459735255 p. [https://books.google.cz/books?id=fHlODQAAQBAJ&pg=PA74 74]. Also {{ISBN|1459735269}}, 9781459735262, [[Google Books]] [https://books.google.cz/books?id=zomGCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT273 PT 273]. \"[...]Goetz returns before calmly stating, \"[...]At this point of the investigation I will be arresting you for murder,[...]\"\"</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Grimaldi, Jeremy|url=https://www.durhamregion.com/news-story/4489558-jennifer-pan-betrays-her-own-web-of-lies-in-videotaped-interview/|title=Jennifer Pan betrays her own 'web of lies' in videotaped interview|website=[[DurhamRegion.com]]|date=2014-04-29|accessdate=2018-09-23|quote=Ms Pan\u2019s dramatic admission came after more than two hours of questioning in a small windowless room at York Police\u2019s markham station}}</ref> During that interview Jennifer admitted that she hired killers, but stated that she hired them to kill herself.<ref name=GrimaldiIthought>{{cite web|last=Grimaldi|first=Jeremy|url=https://www.yorkregion.com/news-story/4490794--i-thought-you-were-on-my-side-pan-tells-york-police/|title='I thought you were on my side', Pan tells York Police|work=[[Markham Economist & Sun]]|date=April 29, 2014|accessdate=September 22, 2018}}</ref> The interrogating police officer, William \"Bill\" Goetz,<ref name=Revenge/><!--for William--><ref name=GrimaldiIthought/><!--for Bill--> falsely told Pan that he had computer software that could analyze untruths in statements and that there were satellites that used [[infrared]] technology to analyze movements in buildings;<ref name=GrimaldiIthought/> in Canada police are legally allowed to lie to those they are interrogating in regards to the evidence in the trial,<ref name=GrimaldiPT62>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735269}}, 9781459735262, [[Google Books]] [https://books.google.com/books?id=zomGCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT62 PT 62]. \"Police in Canada might be allowed to lie to suspects about the evidence they have collected,[...]\"</ref> as well as in regards to the strategies they are using.<ref>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735269}}, 9781459735262, [[Google Books]] [https://books.google.com/books?id=zomGCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT50 PT50]. \"In 2000, the Supreme Court of Canada ruled that police are allowed to lie not only about evidence but tactics, as well.\"</ref> Goetz had used the [[Reid technique]] to ensnare Jennifer.<ref>{{cite news|last=Grimaldi|first=Jeremy|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/insight/2016/11/13/youre-a-good-person-thats-made-a-mistake-here.html|title=The story behind the confession of Jennifer Pan |newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|date=November 13, 2016}} - An excerpt of the book ''[[A Daughter's Deadly Deception]]''.</ref>\n\nMylvaganam was arrested at the [[Jane Finch Mall]] in [[North York, Toronto]] on April 14, 2011. Carty was arrested at the prison he was held in, [[Maplehurst Correctional Complex]] in [[Milton, Ontario]], on April 15, 2011.<ref>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735269}}, 9781459735262, [https://books.google.com/books?id=zomGCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT89 PT89]. \"Two days after speaking with Denise Brown, Detective Courtice gives the order to take David down.[...]The following day, police descend on Maplehurst Correctional[...]where Eric Carty is held, and charge him with the same.\" [https://books.google.com/books?id=zomGCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT88 PT88] states: \"[...]on April 12, when police finally get in touch with Denise Brown,[...]\"</ref> Wong was arrested on April 26, 2011 at his place of employment.<ref name=GrimaldiPT90/> Crawford was the final suspect arrested, entering custody on May 4, 2011 in Brampton.<ref>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735250}}, 9781459735255, p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=fHlODQAAQBAJ&pg=PA109 109]. Also: {{ISBN|1459735269}}, 9781459735262, [https://books.google.cz/books?id=zomGCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT91 PT 91]. \"Lenford is arrested on May 4[...]Brampton driveway.[...]no further charges are laid in his case.\"</ref>\n\n==Trial==\nThe trial of Pan and her accomplices began on March 19, 2014 in [[Newmarket, Ontario|Newmarket]] and continued for ten months. All pleaded not guilty to the charges of [[Murder|first degree murder]], [[attempted murder]], and [[Conspiracy to murder|conspiracy to commit murder]]. At the trial, [[York Regional Police]] evidence included exhaustive tracking of the mobile device movements and text message traffic, including over 100 messages sent between Pan and Wong in the six hours prior to the killing.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://casefilepodcast.com/case-50-jennifer-pan/|title=Case 50: Jennifer Pan - Casefile: True Crime Podcast|date=2017-04-16|work=Casefile: True Crime Podcast|access-date=2018-02-13|language=en-US}}</ref> Further evidence centered around the atypical nature of the \"break-in\", \"robbery\", shootings, and irregularities in Pan's testimony. Pan's obsession with Wong, her lack of true emotion and a confession regarding the attack, and recognition of the [[Tiger mother|trauma she underwent]] were also detailed.<ref name=\":0\" /> A major irregularity was that Pan was not assaulted, blindfolded, taken to the basement, nor shot, leaving behind an eyewitness to the attack. Evidence from Hann, which differed greatly from Pan's version, also undermined her credibility, as did her inability to recreate the conditions of her 9-1-1 call when her hands were bound behind her (given that the police were the ones who had actually cut the shoelace to release her).<ref name=\":0\" /> The trial included over 200 exhibits; over 50 witnesses testified at the trial.<ref name=Revenge/>\n\nPan, Wong, Mylvaganam and Crawford were all convicted on December 13, 2014, and each received a life sentence with no chance of parole for 25 years.<ref name=\"Revenge\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/toronto/jennifer-pan-toronto-woman-whose-plot-to-kill-parents-left-mother-dead-gets-life-in-prison|title=Jennifer Pan, Toronto woman whose plot to kill parents left mother dead, gets life in prison|author=Paola Loriggio, The Canadian Press|date=24 January 2015|work=National Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/jennifer-pan-sentenced-to-life-without-parole-for-25-years-1.2930113|title=Jennifer Pan sentenced to life without parole for 25 years|date=23 January 2015|work=cbc.ca}}</ref><ref name=GrimaldiLifesent>{{cite news|author=Grimaldi, Jeremy|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/2015/01/23/convicted-mother-killer-jennifer-pan-hears-sentence.html|title=Jennifer Pan: Life with no parole for 25 years in murder of mother, attempted murder of father|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|date=23 January 2015|quote=[...]including a non-communication request from Hann Pan, Felix Pan and other family members, banning Pan from contacting any of them.[...]But Justice Crawford disregarded this and went ahead with the ban.}}</ref>\n\nOriginally Carty was tried with the other perpetrators. [[Edward Sapiano]], Carty's lawyer fell ill,<ref name=Dimannoastonishing/> so around the Summer of 2014<!--\"mid-2014\"--> his case was declared a mistrial. In December 2015, Carty received an 18-year sentence after pleading guilty to conspiring to commit murder. He was to be eligible for parole after nine years. According to Carty, he did not wish to subject Hann Pan to another criminal trial<!--\"[...]said he wanted to put an end to Hann's suffering by pleading out to avoid another lengthy trial.\"-->.<ref name=Grimaldi18years/>\n\n===Penalties and imprisonment===\nJennifer Pan was sentenced to life with no parole for 25 years for the murder of her mother, and attempted murder of her father. Pan's father and brother requested a court order that banned Jennifer Pan from contacting members of her surviving family. Despite the objections of the defense lawyers, the judge filed the order.<ref name=GrimaldiLifesent/> Pan is also barred from contacting Wong.<ref name=Grimaldip314alone>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735250}}, 9781459735255 p. [https://books.google.cz/books?id=fHlODQAAQBAJ&pg=PA314 314].</ref>\n\n{{Asof|2016}} Pan was serving her sentence at the [[Grand Valley Institution for Women]] in [[Kitchener, Ontario]].<ref name=Grimaldip313andPT273>Grimaldi, 1459735250, 9781459735255 p. [https://books.google.cz/books?id=fHlODQAAQBAJ&pg=PA313 313], or {{ISBN|1459735269}}, 9781459735262 [[Google Books]] [https://books.google.cz/books?id=zomGCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT273 PT273].</ref> Wong, previously held in [[Lindsay, Ontario]], was at [[Collins Bay Institution]] in [[Kingston, Ontario]]. Mylvaganam was at [[Atlantic Institution]] in [[Renous, New Brunswick]].<ref name=Grimaldip312alone>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735250}}, 9781459735255 p. [https://books.google.cz/books?id=fHlODQAAQBAJ&pg=PA312 312].</ref> Crawford was at [[Kent Institution]] in [[Agassiz, British Columbia]].<ref name=Grimaldip313alone>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735250}}, 9781459735255 p. [https://books.google.cz/books?id=fHlODQAAQBAJ&pg=PA313 313].</ref> Carty, who requested to go to a federal prison in Western Canada or Atlantic Canada, was still at the provincial [[Millhaven Assessment Unit]], awaiting his transfer to a federal prison.<ref name=Grimaldip313andPT273/> Carty, who later moved to Kent, died in his cell on April 26, 2018.<ref name=GrimaldiCartydead/>\n\n==Media reaction==\nAccording to the ''[[South China Morning Post]]'', the case \"sent shockwaves across Canada and the Asian [[diaspora]].\"<ref name=\"LauImmigrantDream\" /> An editorial in the ''[[Northwest Asian Weekly]]'' suggested consideration of the \"idea of recognizing the mental and psychological symptoms that parenting may have gone too far\" in the Pan household.<ref name=\"LoveHate\">{{cite news|last1=Editorial|title=Is it possible to love and hate?|url=http://nwasianweekly.com/2015/08/editorial-is-it-possible-to-love-and-hate-the-strange-case-of-jennifer-pan/|accessdate=9 January 2017|work=[[Northwest Asian Weekly]]|date=15 August 2015}} - [https://search.proquest.com/docview/1706574280 Also at] [[ProQuest]]</ref> A story by Karen K. Ho in ''[[Toronto Life]]'' magazine brought the story to widespread attention by framing it an instance of tiger parenting gone tragically wrong.<ref name=\"Revenge\" /><ref name=\"WangGoldenDaughter\" /><ref name=\"LoveHate\" /> In 2016, journalist Jeremy Grimaldi published a [[true crime]] book about Pan called ''[[A Daughter's Deadly Deception|A Daughter's Deadly Deception: The Jennifer Pan Story]]''.<ref name=\"LauImmigrantDream\" /><ref name=\"BrownChineseCubs\"/> The ''[[Casefile True Crime Podcast|Casefile]]'' and ''[[My Favorite Murder]]'' [[podcasts]] and the ''[[Deadly Women]]'' series also covered the case.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Aftermath==\nBich-Ha Pan's funeral was held on November 15, 2010 and took place at the Ogden Chapel in Scarborough. A funeral for Bich Ha's father was held prior to satisfy a Vietnamese custom that asks for older members of the family to have their funerals first. Jennifer Pan had organized both funerals and had been asked to do so.<!--\"[...]something she later complains her father left her to organize all by herself.\"--><ref>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735269}}, 9781459735262, [[Google Books]] [https://books.google.cz/books?id=zomGCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT49 PT49].</ref> Bich-Ha was buried on November 19.<!--\"Three days after burying her mother, on November 22, Jennifer receives a phone call[...]she has to come in again to speak with the police.\"--><ref>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735269}}, 9781459735262, [[Google Books]] [https://books.google.cz/books?id=zomGCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT50 PT50].</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Bart Whitaker]] \u2013 A Texas man who ordered a hit on his family after he faked continuing attending a university<!--He had dropped out: https://www.cbsnews.com/news/bart-whitaker-execution-reprieve-greg-abbott/ \"Unknown to his parents, the dinner celebration marking his graduation was a fraud. He'd dropped out of school months earlier.\" -->\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n* Grimaldi, Jeremy. ''[[A Daughter's Deadly Deception: The Jennifer Pan Story]]''. [[Dundurn Books]], November 12, 2016.\n** {{ISBN|1459735269}}, 9781459735262.\n** {{ISBN|1459735250}}, 9781459735255.\n\n=== Reference notes ===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.yorkregion.com/yorkregion-topics/4420090-pan-murder-trial/ Index of articles] - ''[[Yorkregion.com]]''\n* [http://casefilepodcast.com/case-49-moors-murders-part-2/ Casefile True Crime Podcast - Case 50: Jennifer Pan] - 15 April 2017\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pan, Jennifer}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Markham, Ontario]]\n[[Category:People from Toronto]]\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Hoa descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian people convicted of murder]]\n[[Category:Matricides]]\n[[Category:Prisoners sentenced to life imprisonment by Canada]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian criminals]]\n[[Category:Prisoners and detainees of Canada]]\n[[Category:Canadian female criminals]]\n[[Category:Canadian female murderers]]\n[[Category:People convicted of murder by Canada]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Vietnamese-Canadian convicted of matricide and attempted patricide}}\n{{Infobox criminal\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name = \n| honorific_suffix = \n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| image = JenniferPan.png\n| image_upright = \n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date =   {{birth date and age|1986|6|17|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], [[Canada]]\n| disappeared_date = \n| disappeared_place = \n| disappeared_status = \n| death_date =     <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| body_discovered = \n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates =\n| monuments = \n| residence = \n| nationality = [[Canadian]]\n| other_names = \n| citizenship = Canada\n| education = [[Mary Ward Catholic Secondary School]] (did not graduate)\n| alma_mater = \n| occupation = \n| years_active = \n| employer = \n| organization = \n| agent = \n| known_for = \n| notable_works = \n| style = \n| home_town = \n| salary = \n| net_worth = \n| height = \n| weight = \n| television = \n| title = \n| term = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| party = \n| movement = \n| opponents = \n| boards = \n| religion = \n| denomination = \n| criminal_charge = {{ublist|First-degree murder|Attempted murder|Conspiracy to commit murder}}\n| conviction_penalty = [[Life imprisonment]] with possibility of parole after 25 years\n| conviction_status = Incarcerated\n| spouse =         <!-- Do not include unless notable or relevant to the crime involved -->\n| children =       <!-- (as above) -->\n| parents = {{ublist|Huei Hann Pan|Bich Ha Pan}}\n| relatives = Felix Pan\n| callsign = \n| awards = \n| website = \n| allegiance = \n| motive = Romantic relationship, monetary gain, alleged child abuse\n| conviction = \n| reward_amount = \n| capture_status = \n| wanted_by = \n| partners = \n| wanted_since = \n| time_at_large = \n| escaped = \n| escape_end = \n| comments = \n| victims = Bich Ha Pan\n| date = November 8, 2010\n| time = \n| beginyear = \n| endyear = \n| country = Canada\n| states = \n| locations = \n| targets = \n| fatalities = \n| injuries = \n| weapons = \n| apprehended = \n| imprisoned = \n| module =\n| signature =\n| signature_size =\n| signature_alt = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''Jennifer Pan''' (born 17 June 1986) is a [[Vietnamese Canadians|Vietnamese-Canadian]] woman of [[Chinese people|Chinese]]-[[Vietnamese people|Vietnamese]] ancestry convicted of a 2010 [[Contract killing|kill-for-hire]] attack targeting both of her parents, in response to their allegedly abusive \"[[tiger parenting]]\" into her mid-20s. The crime took place at the Pan residence in [[Unionville, Ontario|Unionville]], [[Markham, Ontario|Markham]], [[Ontario]], in the [[Greater Toronto Area]]. Jeremy Grimaldi, a journalist of the ''[[Markham Economist & Sun]]'' and the author of ''[[A Daughter's Deadly Deception: The Jennifer Pan Story]]'', stated that the affair \"captivated many, if for nothing else than the sheer intrigue of a case involving [[matricide]], a rarity in Canada.\"<ref name=Grimaldi18years>{{cite news|last=Grimaldi|first=Jeremy|url=https://www.yorkregion.com/news-story/6163269-carty-gets-18-years-for-his-part-in-markham-s-pan-murder/|title=Carty gets 18 years for his part in Markham's Pan murder|work=[[Markham Economist & Sun]]|date=December 7, 2015|accessdate=September 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nJennifer Pan's mother Bich Ha (pronounced \"Bick\"){{#tag:ref|''Bich Ha Pan'': {{zh|first=c,j|c=\u6881\u78a7\u971e|j=loeng4 bik1 haa4|p=Li\u00e1ng B\u00ecxi\u00e1}}<ref name=ZHnameparents>Source of Chinese names: {{cite web|url=http://news.singtao.ca/toronto/content_column_tor.php?IndexID=2863523|title=\u300c\u4e56\u4e56\u5973\u300d\u88ab\u63a7\u5f12\u6bcd.\u842c\u9326\u5165\u5c4b\u52ab\u6bba\u6848\u5cf0\u8ff4\u8def\u8f49|work=[[Sing Tao Daily (Canada)|Sing Tao]]|date=November 24, 2010|accessdate=September 18, 2018}}</ref>|group=note}} and father Huei Hann Pan{{#tag:ref|''Huei Hann Pan'': {{zh|first=t,j||t=\u6f58\u6f22\u8f1d|s=\u6f58\u6c49\u8f89|j=pun1 hon3 fai1|p=P\u0101n H\u00e0nhu\u012b}}<ref name=ZHnameparents/>|group=note}} were Sino-Vietnamese ([[Viet Hoa]]) immigrants to Canada.<ref name=LauImmigrantDream>{{cite news|last1=Lau|first1=Joyce|title=A murder in Toronto and the dark side of the Asian immigrant dream (book review)|url=http://www.scmp.com/magazines/post-magazine/books/article/2043688/murder-toronto-and-dark-side-asian-immigrant-dream|accessdate=9 January 2017|newspaper=[[South China Morning Post]]|date=8 November 2016}}</ref> Hann was born and educated in [[Vietnam]], moving to Canada in 1979 as a [[political refugee]]. Bich also immigrated as a refugee. The couple were married in [[Toronto]] and lived in [[Scarborough, Toronto|Scarborough]]. Their two children are Jennifer, born 1986, and Felix, born 1989.<ref name=\"Revenge\">{{cite magazine|last1=Ho|first1=Karen K.|date=22 July 2015|title=Jennifer Pan's Revenge: The inside story of a golden child, the killers she hired, and the parents she wanted dead|url=http://torontolife.com/city/crime/jennifer-pan-revenge/|magazine=[[Toronto Life]]|accessdate=9 January 2017}} - [https://torontolife.com/city/jennifer-pan-revenge-simplified-chinese-translation/ Version in Simplified Chinese]<!--Old URL: http://web.archive.org/web/20150722213215/http://www.torontolife.com/informer/features/2015/07/22/jennifer-pan-revenge-simplified-chinese-translation/--></ref><ref name=WangGoldenDaughter>{{cite news|last1=Wang|first1=Yanan|title=Tragedy of 'golden' daughter's fall resonates with Asian immigrant children|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2015/07/27/tragedy-of-golden-daughters-murder-plot-against-parents-resonates-with-asian-immigrant-children/|accessdate=9 January 2017|newspaper=[[Washington Post]]|date=27 July 2015}}</ref> The Pans found work at [[Magna International]], an auto parts manufacturer in [[Aurora, Ontario|Aurora]], [[Ontario]].<ref name=Revenge/> Hann worked as a tool and die maker, while Bich made car parts. The couple persistently worked hard for their money to ensure that their children had the upbringing and opportunities they themselves had missed out on. Hann and Bich were thrifty and by 2004 were financially stable enough to purchase a \"large\" house with a two-car garage on a residential street in [[Markham, Ontario|Markham]], a town with a large Asian population.<ref name=LauImmigrantDream/> Bich drove a [[Lexus ES 300]] and Hann drove a [[Mercedes-Benz C-Class (W203)]]. They had accumulated [[Canadian dollar|CAD$]]200,000 in savings.<ref name=Revenge/>\n\nJennifer's parents set many goals for their children and had extremely high expectations of them. Jennifer was made to take piano lessons at the age of four, as well as [[figure skating]] classes where she trained most days during the week. She had hopes of becoming an [[Olympic Games|Olympic]] figure skating champion until she tore a ligament in her knee. Jennifer attended [[Mary Ward Catholic Secondary School]] where she played the [[flute]] in the school band.<ref name=Revenge/> According to her high school friend Karen K. Ho, Hann was seen as \"the classic [[tiger parenting|tiger dad]],\" and Bich was \"his reluctant accomplice.\" The Pans picked Jennifer up when classes ended each day and monitored her extracurricular activities very closely. They never permitted her to date boys while attending high school, or to attend high school dances or [[prom]]s out of fear that these activities would distract her from her academic commitments. Jennifer was not permitted to attend any parties while her parents believed that she was attending university. At the age of 22, \"she had never gone to a club, been drunk, visited a friend's cottage or gone on vacation without her family.\"<ref name=Revenge/> Jennifer and her friends reportedly regarded this upbringing as restrictive and greatly oppressive.<ref name=Revenge/>\n\nDespite her parents' high expectations and the fact that Jennifer had received good grades in lower school, throughout high school her grades were somewhat average (in the 70% range) except for music. Multiple times, she forged [[report card]]s using false templates to show her parents that she had received straight As when she had not. When Jennifer failed calculus class in her senior year of high school, [[Ryerson University]] rescinded her early admission. As she could not bear to be perceived as a failure, she began to lie to those she knew, including her parents, and pretended she was attending university. Instead, she sat in caf\u00e9s, taught as a piano instructor and worked in a restaurant to earn money. In order to maintain the charade, Jennifer told her parents she had won scholarships, later falsely claiming that she had accepted an offer into the pharmacology program at the [[University of Toronto]]. She went to the extent of purchasing second-hand textbooks and watching videos related to pharmacology in order to create notebooks full of purported class notes that she could show her parents. Jennifer also requested permission from her parents to stay near the campus with a friend throughout the week.<ref name=Revenge/>\n\nJennifer was actually staying with her boyfriend,<ref name=Revenge/> Daniel Chi-Kwong Wong,{{#tag:ref|''Daniel Chi-Kwong Wong'': {{zh|first=t,j|t=\u9ec3\u5fd7\u5149|s=\u9ec4\u5fd7\u5149|j=wong4 zi3 gwong1|p=Hu\u00e1ng Zh\u00ecgu\u0101ng|labels=no}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.singtao.ca/toronto/2014-05-10/city1399706077d5044769.html|title=\u7537\u53cb\u7206\u6f58\u5973\u66fe\u906d5\u6f22\u6027\u4fb5 \u8072\u7a31\u6536\u8b66\u544a\u77ed\u8a0a \u77e2\u53e3\u5426\u8a8d\u6d89\u6848|work=[[Sing Tao Daily]]|date=2014-05-10|accessdate=2018-09-18}}</ref>|group=note}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/4th-arrest-in-markham-home-invasion-homicide-1.1038532|agency=[[The Canadian Press]]|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]]|title=4th arrest in Markham home invasion homicide|date=2011-04-26|accessdate=2018-09-18}}</ref> a high school sweetheart whom her parents knew nothing about.<ref name=Revenge/><ref name=\"BrownChineseCubs\">{{cite news|last1=Brown|first1=Vanessa|title=When Chinese cubs turn on their Tiger Parents|url=http://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/real-life/true-stories/when-chinese-cubs-turn-on-their-tiger-parents/news-story/36ad884522b2d22ba1e2f88faa5d72ab|accessdate=9 January 2017|work=News.com.au|date=11 December 2016}}</ref><ref>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735269}}, 9781459735262, [[Google Books]] [https://books.google.com/books?id=zomGCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT31 PT 31]: \"[...]commenting on the fact that he was only half Chinese. \"[...]you're [part] Filipino.\"\"</ref> Wong was of mixed Chinese and [[Filipino people|Filipino]] ancestry,<ref name=\"BrownChineseCubs\">{{cite news|last1=Brown|first1=Vanessa|title=When Chinese cubs turn on their Tiger Parents|url=http://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/real-life/true-stories/when-chinese-cubs-turn-on-their-tiger-parents/news-story/36ad884522b2d22ba1e2f88faa5d72ab|accessdate=9 January 2017|work=News.com.au|date=11 December 2016}}</ref><ref>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735269}}, 9781459735262, [[Google Books]] [https://books.google.es/books?id=zomGCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT31 PT 31]: \"[...]commenting on the fact that he was only half Chinese. \"[...]you're [part] Filipino.\"\"</ref> resided in [[Ajax, Ontario|Ajax]],<ref name=GillisWendyFifth>{{cite news|author=Gillis, Wendy|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/crime/2011/05/04/fifth_suspect_arrested_in_deadly_markham_home_invasion.html|title=Fifth suspect arrested in deadly Markham home invasion |newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|date=May 4, 2011|accessdate=September 18, 2018}}</ref> and worked at a [[Boston Pizza]] restaurant.<ref name=GrimaldiPT90>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735269}}, 9781459735262, [https://books.google.cz/books?id=zomGCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT90 PT 90]. \"Daniel Wong is arrested at work in front of his colleagues at Boston Pizza on April 26, 2011.\"</ref> Wong, once a student at Mary Ward, transferred to [[Cardinal Carter Academy]] in North York, Toronto due to low grades<!--\"he was falling behind\"-->, and later studied at [[York University]].<ref name=Revenge/> He was an active [[marijuana]] dealer.<ref name=Revenge/><!--\"he had been charged with trafficking after cops found half a pound of weed in his car.\"--><ref name=Dimannoastonishing>{{cite news|last=Dimanno|first=Rosie|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/crime/2014/09/15/the_fantastic_testimony_of_jennifer_pan.html|title=The astonishing testimony of Jennifer Pan|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|date=September 15, 2014|accessdate=September 25, 2018|quote=Seven years until Wong \u2014 Pan says he was the one who put her in touch with \u201cHomeboy,\u201d a man he knew through his marijuana dealing}}</ref>\n\n==Adult life==\nWhile pretending to complete her degree at the University of Toronto, Jennifer told her parents that she had started working as a volunteer at Toronto's [[The Hospital for Sick Children, Toronto|Hospital for Sick Children]], known as Sick Kids. Hann and Bich soon became suspicious when they realized she did not have a hospital ID badge or uniform. On one occasion, Bich followed her daughter to \"work\" and quickly discovered her deception. In a state of shock, Hann wanted to throw Jennifer out of the house, but her mother persuaded him to allow her to stay. As she had not completed high school due to failing calculus, she eventually began working to finish high school completely and was later encouraged by her parents to apply to university. She was, however, forbidden to contact Wong or to go anywhere except to her piano-teaching job. Nevertheless, she and Wong spoke clandestinely during this period.<ref name=Revenge/>\n\nBy the time that Jennifer was 24, Wong had grown weary of trying to pursue a relationship with Jennifer. As she was so daunted and restricted by her parents that she lived at home and only met him in secret, Wong began to date another young woman whom he soon fell in love with.<ref name=Revenge/> Jennifer quickly invented a new story and told Wong that a man had entered her house, showing what appeared to be a police badge. She then told him that several men had rushed in and [[gang rape]]d her. After this, Jennifer insisted that a bullet was mailed to her, telling Wong that it was sent from his new girlfriend.<ref name=Revenge/>\n\n==Murder==\nIn Spring 2010, Jennifer was in contact with Andrew Montemayor, a high school friend who, she claims, had boasted in their high school years about robbing people at knife point, an assertion denied by Montemayor. Montemayor introduced her to Ricardo Duncan, a \"[[Goth subculture|goth]] kid\" whom Pan gave $1,500 to [[contract killing|kill her father]] in the parking lot at his workplace. Duncan says that she once gave him $200 for a night out, but that he returned it, and that he rebuffed her when she asked him to kill her parents.<ref name=Revenge/>\n\nJennifer and Wong were back in contact at this time and according to the police, came up with a plan to hire a professional [[hitman]] for $10,000 to kill her parents, calculating that she would then inherit $500,000. They planned to move in together. Wong connected Pan with a man,<ref name=Revenge/> Lenford Roy Crawford,<ref name=GillisWendyFifth/> Jamaican-born,<ref>Grimaldi, ''[[A Daughter's Deadly Deception]]'', {{ISBN|1459735250}}, 9781459735255, p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=fHlODQAAQBAJ&pg=PA81 81].</ref> whom he called \"Homeboy\", and gave her a [[SIM card]] and an [[iPhone]] so that she could contact Crawford without using her usual cell phone.<ref name=Revenge/> Crawford contacted another man,<ref name=HashamCrownfinishpres>{{cite news|last=Hasham|first=Alyshah|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/crime/2014/08/13/crown_finishes_presenting_evidence_against_jennifer_pan_in_murder_trial.html|title=Crown finishes presenting evidence against Jennifer Pan in murder trial|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|date=August 13, 2014|accessdate=September 20, 2018|quote=[...]who in turn involved David Mylvaganam, allegedly one of three men who[...]It remains unclear who the other two men who entered the house are. The jury has heard that Crawford and Wong were both at work at the time of the murder. }}</ref> named Eric Shawn \"Sniper\" Carty,<ref name=GrimaldiCartydead>{{cite web|last=Grimaldi|first=Jeremy|url=https://www.yorkregion.com/news-story/8680927-eric-carty-linchpin-in-jennifer-pan-murder-plot-dies-in-jail/|title=Eric Carty, linchpin in Jennifer Pan murder plot, dies in jail|work=[[Markham Economist & Sun]]|date=2018-06-26|accessdate=2018-09-29}}</ref> who in turn contacted [[Montreal]]-born David Mylvaganam.<ref name=HashamCrownfinishpres/><ref name=\"LauImmigrantDream\" /> Crawford lived in [[Brampton, Ontario|Brampton]] and Mylvaganam lived in Toronto, while Carty,<ref name=GillisWendyFifth/> who previously lived in [[Rexdale, Toronto]],<ref name=GrimaldiCartydead/> at the time did not have a fixed residence.<ref name=GillisWendyFifth/> The [[The Crown|Crown]] stated that Mylvaganam was one of the hitmen.<ref name=HashamCrownfinishpres/> Carty was later found responsible for an unrelated murder, and Grimaldi stated that Carty was \"a repeat violent offender\".<ref name=Grimaldi18years/>\n\nThe murder took place at the Pan residence in [[Unionville, Ontario|Unionville]], in Markham.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.guelphmercury.com/news-story/4431797-markham-murder-trial-resumes-with-father-still-on-stand/|title=Markham murder trial resumes with father still on stand|agency=[[Markham Economist & Sun]]|work=[[Guelph Mercury Tribune]]|date=March 26, 2014|accessdate=September 19, 2018|quote=[...]in Unionville in this file photograph. This was the scene of the murder of Bich Pan in 2010.}}</ref> On November 8, 2010, Jennifer unlocked the front door of the family home when she went to bed, then spoke by phone to Mylvaganam. Shortly afterwards, Mylvaganam and two other people [[home invasion|entered the home]] through the unlocked front door, all carrying guns.<ref name=Revenge/> In court testimony, the Crown did not establish the identity of the other two hitmen; Wong and Crawford were at work.<ref name=HashamCrownfinishpres/> Carty stated that he was the driver for those who broke into the house, and that he selected them and was involved in plotting the attack. He did not state that he was one of the three or that he directly attacked others.<ref name=Grimaldi18years/> Grimaldi stated that the identity of the triggerperson remains unknown.<ref name=Grimaldi18years/><!--\"To this day, it remains unclear who pulled the trigger,[...]\"-->\n\nAfter demanding all the money in the house and ransacking the main bedroom, the three men took Bich and Hann to the basement where they shot them multiple times. Bich was killed but Hann would survive his wounds. The three men then took all the cash that was in the house, including $2,000 from Jennifer, and left. Jennifer claimed that they tied her up, but that she managed to free her hands and dial [[9-1-1]].<ref name=Revenge/> Hann was treated at [[Markham Stouffville Hospital]],<ref name=Grimaldip17alone>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735250}}, 9781459735255 p. [https://books.google.cz/books?id=fHlODQAAQBAJ&pg=PA17 17].</ref> before being moved to a trauma unit<ref name=Grimaldip27alone>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735250}}, 9781459735255 p. [https://books.google.cz/books?id=fHlODQAAQBAJ&pg=PA27 27].</ref> at [[Sunnybrook Hospital]] in Toronto by aircraft.<ref name=Grimaldip35alone>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735250}}, 9781459735255 p. [https://books.google.cz/books?id=fHlODQAAQBAJ&pg=PA35 35].</ref><ref name=Grimaldip27alone/>\n\n== Investigation and arrests ==\nThe evening after the murder, Jennifer underwent her first interview with the police.<ref name=Grimaldip18alone>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735250}}, 9781459735255 p. [https://books.google.cz/books?id=fHlODQAAQBAJ&pg=PA18 18].</ref> She was arrested on November 22, 2010<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/jennifer-pan-plotted-to-have-parents-killed-says-crown-1.2579135|title=Jennifer Pan plotted to have parents killed, says Crown|agency=[[The Canadian Press]]|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]]|date=March 19, 2014|accessdate=September 18, 2018}}</ref> during her third interview at the Markham police station (5 District) of [[York Regional Police]].<ref name=Grimaldiinterviewarrest>Grimaldi - Interview date: {{ISBN|1459735250}}, 9781459735255 p. [https://books.google.cz/books?id=fHlODQAAQBAJ&pg=PA66 66]. \"During her third police interview, on November 22, 2016, Jennifer opens up to Detective Goetz[...]\" - Arrest: {{ISBN|1459735250}}, 9781459735255 p. [https://books.google.cz/books?id=fHlODQAAQBAJ&pg=PA74 74]. Also {{ISBN|1459735269}}, 9781459735262, [[Google Books]] [https://books.google.cz/books?id=zomGCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT273 PT 273]. \"[...]Goetz returns before calmly stating, \"[...]At this point of the investigation I will be arresting you for murder,[...]\"\"</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Grimaldi, Jeremy|url=https://www.durhamregion.com/news-story/4489558-jennifer-pan-betrays-her-own-web-of-lies-in-videotaped-interview/|title=Jennifer Pan betrays her own 'web of lies' in videotaped interview|website=[[DurhamRegion.com]]|date=2014-04-29|accessdate=2018-09-23|quote=Ms Pan\u2019s dramatic admission came after more than two hours of questioning in a small windowless room at York Police\u2019s markham station}}</ref> During that interview Pan admitted that she hired killers, but stated that she hired them to kill her.<ref name=GrimaldiIthought>{{cite web|last=Grimaldi|first=Jeremy|url=https://www.yorkregion.com/news-story/4490794--i-thought-you-were-on-my-side-pan-tells-york-police/|title='I thought you were on my side', Pan tells York Police|work=[[Markham Economist & Sun]]|date=April 29, 2014|accessdate=September 22, 2018}}</ref> The interrogating police officer, William \"Bill\" Goetz,<ref name=Revenge/><!--for William--><ref name=GrimaldiIthought/><!--for Bill--> falsely told Pan that he had computer software that could analyze untruths in statements and that there were satellites that used [[infrared]] technology to analyze movements in buildings;<ref name=GrimaldiIthought/> in Canada police are legally allowed to lie to those they are interrogating in regards to the evidence in the trial,<ref name=GrimaldiPT62>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735269}}, 9781459735262, [[Google Books]] [https://books.google.com/books?id=zomGCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT62 PT 62]. \"Police in Canada might be allowed to lie to suspects about the evidence they have collected,[...]\"</ref> as well as in regards to the strategies they are using.<ref>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735269}}, 9781459735262, [[Google Books]] [https://books.google.com/books?id=zomGCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT50 PT50]. \"In 2000, the Supreme Court of Canada ruled that police are allowed to lie not only about evidence but tactics, as well.\"</ref> Goetz had used the [[Reid technique]] to ensnare Pan.<ref>{{cite news|last=Grimaldi|first=Jeremy|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/insight/2016/11/13/youre-a-good-person-thats-made-a-mistake-here.html|title=The story behind the confession of Jennifer Pan |newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|date=November 13, 2016}} - An excerpt of the book ''[[A Daughter's Deadly Deception]]''.</ref>\n\nMylvaganam was arrested at the [[Jane Finch Mall]] in [[North York, Toronto]] on April 14, 2011. Carty was arrested at the prison he was held in, [[Maplehurst Correctional Complex]] in [[Milton, Ontario]], on April 15, 2011.<ref>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735269}}, 9781459735262, [https://books.google.com/books?id=zomGCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT89 PT89]. \"Two days after speaking with Denise Brown, Detective Courtice gives the order to take David down.[...]The following day, police descend on Maplehurst Correctional[...]where Eric Carty is held, and charge him with the same.\" [https://books.google.com/books?id=zomGCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT88 PT88] states: \"[...]on April 12, when police finally get in touch with Denise Brown,[...]\"</ref> Wong was arrested on April 26, 2011 at his place of employment.<ref name=GrimaldiPT90/> Crawford was the final suspect arrested, entering custody on May 4, 2011 in Brampton.<ref>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735250}}, 9781459735255, p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=fHlODQAAQBAJ&pg=PA109 109]. Also: {{ISBN|1459735269}}, 9781459735262, [https://books.google.cz/books?id=zomGCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT91 PT 91]. \"Lenford is arrested on May 4[...]Brampton driveway.[...]no further charges are laid in his case.\"</ref>\n\n==Trial==\nThe trial of Pan and her accomplices began on March 19, 2014 in [[Newmarket, Ontario|Newmarket]] and continued for ten months. All pleaded not guilty to the charges of [[Murder|first degree murder]], [[attempted murder]], and [[Conspiracy to murder|conspiracy to commit murder]]. At the trial, [[York Regional Police]] evidence included exhaustive tracking of the mobile device movements and text message traffic, including over 100 messages sent between Pan and Wong in the six hours prior to the killing.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://casefilepodcast.com/case-50-jennifer-pan/|title=Case 50: Jennifer Pan - Casefile: True Crime Podcast|date=2017-04-16|work=Casefile: True Crime Podcast|access-date=2018-02-13|language=en-US}}</ref> Further evidence centered around the atypical nature of the \"break-in\", \"robbery\", shootings, and irregularities in Pan's testimony. Pan's obsession with Wong, her lack of true emotion and a confession regarding the attack, and recognition of the [[Tiger mother|trauma she underwent]] were also detailed.<ref name=\":0\" /> A major irregularity was that Pan was not assaulted, blindfolded, taken to the basement, nor shot, leaving behind an eyewitness to the attack. Evidence from Hann, which differed greatly from Pan's version, also undermined her credibility, as did her inability to recreate the conditions of her 9-1-1 call when her hands were bound behind her (given that the police were the ones who had actually cut the shoelace to release her).<ref name=\":0\" /> The trial included over 200 exhibits; over 50 witnesses testified at the trial.<ref name=Revenge/>\n\nPan, Wong, Mylvaganam and Crawford were all convicted on December 13, 2014, and each received a life sentence with no chance of parole for 25 years.<ref name=\"Revenge\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/toronto/jennifer-pan-toronto-woman-whose-plot-to-kill-parents-left-mother-dead-gets-life-in-prison|title=Jennifer Pan, Toronto woman whose plot to kill parents left mother dead, gets life in prison|author=Paola Loriggio, The Canadian Press|date=24 January 2015|work=National Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/jennifer-pan-sentenced-to-life-without-parole-for-25-years-1.2930113|title=Jennifer Pan sentenced to life without parole for 25 years|date=23 January 2015|work=cbc.ca}}</ref><ref name=GrimaldiLifesent>{{cite news|author=Grimaldi, Jeremy|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/2015/01/23/convicted-mother-killer-jennifer-pan-hears-sentence.html|title=Jennifer Pan: Life with no parole for 25 years in murder of mother, attempted murder of father|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|date=23 January 2015|quote=[...]including a non-communication request from Hann Pan, Felix Pan and other family members, banning Pan from contacting any of them.[...]But Justice Crawford disregarded this and went ahead with the ban.}}</ref>\n\nOriginally Carty was tried with the other perpetrators. [[Edward Sapiano]], Carty's lawyer fell ill,<ref name=Dimannoastonishing/> so around the Summer of 2014<!--\"mid-2014\"--> his case was declared a mistrial. In December 2015, Carty received an 18-year sentence after pleading guilty to conspiring to commit murder. He was to be eligible for parole after nine years. According to Carty, he did not wish to subject Hann Pan to another criminal trial<!--\"[...]said he wanted to put an end to Hann's suffering by pleading out to avoid another lengthy trial.\"-->.<ref name=Grimaldi18years/>\n\n===Penalties and imprisonment===\nJennifer Pan was sentenced to life with no parole for 25 years for the murder of her mother, and attempted murder of her father. Pan's father and brother requested a court order that banned Jennifer Pan from contacting members of her surviving family. Despite the objections of the defense lawyers, the judge filed the order.<ref name=GrimaldiLifesent/> Pan is also barred from contacting Wong.<ref name=Grimaldip314alone>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735250}}, 9781459735255 p. [https://books.google.cz/books?id=fHlODQAAQBAJ&pg=PA314 314].</ref>\n\n{{Asof|2016}} Pan was serving her sentence at the [[Grand Valley Institution for Women]] in [[Kitchener, Ontario]].<ref name=Grimaldip313andPT273>Grimaldi, 1459735250, 9781459735255 p. [https://books.google.cz/books?id=fHlODQAAQBAJ&pg=PA313 313], or {{ISBN|1459735269}}, 9781459735262 [[Google Books]] [https://books.google.cz/books?id=zomGCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT273 PT273].</ref> Wong, previously held in [[Lindsay, Ontario]], was at [[Collins Bay Institution]] in [[Kingston, Ontario]]. Mylvaganam was at [[Atlantic Institution]] in [[Renous, New Brunswick]].<ref name=Grimaldip312alone>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735250}}, 9781459735255 p. [https://books.google.cz/books?id=fHlODQAAQBAJ&pg=PA312 312].</ref> Crawford was at [[Kent Institution]] in [[Agassiz, British Columbia]].<ref name=Grimaldip313alone>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735250}}, 9781459735255 p. [https://books.google.cz/books?id=fHlODQAAQBAJ&pg=PA313 313].</ref> Carty, who requested to go to a federal prison in Western Canada or Atlantic Canada, was still at the provincial [[Millhaven Assessment Unit]], awaiting his transfer to a federal prison.<ref name=Grimaldip313andPT273/> Carty, who later moved to Kent, died in his cell on April 26, 2018.<ref name=GrimaldiCartydead/>\n\n==Media reaction==\nAccording to the ''[[South China Morning Post]]'', the case \"sent shockwaves across Canada and the Asian [[diaspora]].\"<ref name=\"LauImmigrantDream\" /> An editorial in the ''[[Northwest Asian Weekly]]'' suggested consideration of the \"idea of recognizing the mental and psychological symptoms that parenting may have gone too far\" in the Pan household.<ref name=\"LoveHate\">{{cite news|last1=Editorial|title=Is it possible to love and hate?|url=http://nwasianweekly.com/2015/08/editorial-is-it-possible-to-love-and-hate-the-strange-case-of-jennifer-pan/|accessdate=9 January 2017|work=[[Northwest Asian Weekly]]|date=15 August 2015}} - [https://search.proquest.com/docview/1706574280 Also at] [[ProQuest]]</ref> A story by Karen K. Ho in ''[[Toronto Life]]'' magazine brought the story to widespread attention by framing it an instance of tiger parenting gone tragically wrong.<ref name=\"Revenge\" /><ref name=\"WangGoldenDaughter\" /><ref name=\"LoveHate\" /> In 2016, journalist Jeremy Grimaldi published a [[true crime]] book about Pan called ''[[A Daughter's Deadly Deception|A Daughter's Deadly Deception: The Jennifer Pan Story]]''.<ref name=\"LauImmigrantDream\" /><ref name=\"BrownChineseCubs\"/> The ''[[Casefile True Crime Podcast|Casefile]]'' and ''[[My Favorite Murder]]'' [[podcasts]] and the ''[[Deadly Women]]'' series also covered the case.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Aftermath==\nBich-Ha Pan's funeral was held on November 15, 2010 and took place at the Ogden Chapel in Scarborough. A funeral for Bich Ha's father was held prior to satisfy a Vietnamese custom that asks for older members of the family to have their funerals first. Jennifer Pan had organized both funerals and had been asked to do so.<!--\"[...]something she later complains her father left her to organize all by herself.\"--><ref>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735269}}, 9781459735262, [[Google Books]] [https://books.google.cz/books?id=zomGCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT49 PT49].</ref> Bich-Ha was buried on November 19.<!--\"Three days after burying her mother, on November 22, Jennifer receives a phone call[...]she has to come in again to speak with the police.\"--><ref>Grimaldi, {{ISBN|1459735269}}, 9781459735262, [[Google Books]] [https://books.google.cz/books?id=zomGCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT50 PT50].</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Bart Whitaker]] \u2013 A Texas man who ordered a hit on his family after he faked continuing attending a university<!--He had dropped out: https://www.cbsnews.com/news/bart-whitaker-execution-reprieve-greg-abbott/ \"Unknown to his parents, the dinner celebration marking his graduation was a fraud. He'd dropped out of school months earlier.\" -->\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n* Grimaldi, Jeremy. ''[[A Daughter's Deadly Deception: The Jennifer Pan Story]]''. [[Dundurn Books]], November 12, 2016.\n** {{ISBN|1459735269}}, 9781459735262.\n** {{ISBN|1459735250}}, 9781459735255.\n\n=== Reference notes ===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.yorkregion.com/yorkregion-topics/4420090-pan-murder-trial/ Index of articles] - ''[[Yorkregion.com]]''\n* [http://casefilepodcast.com/case-49-moors-murders-part-2/ Casefile True Crime Podcast - Case 50: Jennifer Pan] - 15 April 2017\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pan, Jennifer}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Markham, Ontario]]\n[[Category:People from Toronto]]\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Hoa descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian people convicted of murder]]\n[[Category:Matricides]]\n[[Category:Prisoners sentenced to life imprisonment by Canada]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian criminals]]\n[[Category:Prisoners and detainees of Canada]]\n[[Category:Canadian female criminals]]\n[[Category:Canadian female murderers]]\n[[Category:People convicted of murder by Canada]]\n", "name_user": "SebastianDrawsStuff", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eInvestigation and arrests", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jennifer_Pan"}
{"title_page": "Bo Winegard", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=April 2020}}\n{{POV|date=April 2020}}\n{{Notability|Academics|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| honorific_prefix  = \n| name              = Bo Winegard\n| honorific_suffix  = \n| native_name       = \n| native_name_lang  = \n| image             = Bo Winegard2.jpg\n| image_size        = \n| image_upright     = \n| alt               = \n| caption           = \n| birth_name        = <!-- if different from \"name\" -->\n| birth_date        = {{birth date and age|1980|01|07}}\n| birth_place       = [[Greenville]], [[Michigan (state)|Michigan]]\n| death_date        = <!--{{death date and age |YYYY|MM|DD |YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date)-->\n| death_place       = \n| death_cause       = \n| resting_place     = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!--{{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}-->\n| other_names       = \n| pronounce         =\n| residence         = \n| citizenship       = \n| nationality       = American\n| fields            = [[Social psychology]]\n| workplaces        = [[Marietta College]]\n| patrons           = \n| education         = \n| alma_mater        = [[Florida State University]]\n| thesis_title      = \n| thesis_url        = \n| thesis_year       = \n| doctoral_advisor  = [[Roy Baumeister]]\n| academic_advisors = \n| doctoral_students = \n| notable_students  = \n| known_for         =\n| influences        = \n| influenced        = \n| awards            = \n| author_abbrev_bot = \n| author_abbrev_zoo = \n| spouse            = <!--(or | spouses = )-->\n| partner           = <!--(or | partners = )-->\n| children          = \n| signature         = <!--(filename only)-->\n| signature_alt     = \n| website           = <!--{{URL|www.example.com}}-->\n| footnotes         = \n}}\n'''Bo Winegard''' (born January 7, 1980) is an American social scientist and contributing writer at popular press outlets such as ''[[Quillette]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://quillette.com/author/bo-winegard/}}</ref> and Arc Digital<ref>{{cite web|url=https://arcdigital.media/@winegabo}}</ref>.\n\n== Career ==\nBo Winegard received his Ph.D. in [[Social Psychology]] from [[Florida State University]] in 2018 under the supervision of Professor [[Roy Baumeister]]. In 2018, he became an Assistant Professor of Psychology at [[Marietta College]], but in 2020, his tenure-track position was terminated without official explanation.<<ref>{{cite web|url=https://quillette.com/2020/03/06/ive-been-fired-if-you-value-academic-freedom-that-should-worry-you/|title=I\u2019ve Been Fired. If You Value Academic Freedom, That Should Worry You|first=Bo|last=Winegard|accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Controversy==\n\nIn late 2019, Winegard was invited to give a talk at the [[University of Alabama]] on \u201cThe Evolution of Human Diversity\u201d.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://as.ua.edu/alumni/event/allele-the-evolution-of-human-diversity-dr-bo-winegard-marietta-college/|title=ALLELE: \"The Evolution of Human Diversity,\" Dr. Bo Winegard (Marietta College)}}</ref> The talk, which addressed the possibility that human populations may have evolved different psychological tendencies, stirred a controversy at the University because of the perceived \u201cracist implications\u201d of the research.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cw.ua.edu/56341/news/evolution-working-group-on-hosting-bo-winegard-it-was-our-mistake/|title=Evolution Working Group on hosting Bo Winegard: \u2018It was our mistake\u2019|first=Jeffrey|last=Kelly|accessdate=7 November 2019}}</ref>{{rs|date=April 2020}} In early 2020, Winegard was fired from his position at [[Marietta College]].\n\nChristopher Ferguson of ''[[Areo (magazine)|Areo]]'' contended that the talk explicitly denounced racism and urged people to treat others as individuals, not tokens of some group or another.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://areomagazine.com/2020/03/16/the-firing-of-bo-winegard-when-academic-freedom-and-outrage-collide/|title=The Firing of Bo Winegard: When Academic Freedom and Outrage Collide|first=Christopher|last=Ferguson|accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref> Some sources suggested that Winegard may have been fired for his \u201crisky research,\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2020/03/12/assistant-professor-says-hes-been-fired-because-he-dared-talk-about-human-population|title=Risky Research|first=Colleen|last=Flaherty|accessdate=12 March 2020}}</ref> \u201cwrongthink,\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thepostmillennial.com/professor-was-fired-from-his-tenure-track-job-for-wrongthink|title=Professor fired from his tenure track job for wrongthink|first=Libby|last=Emmons|accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref>{{rs|certain=y|date=April 2020}} \u201ccontroversial race theories,\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2020/mar/13/bo-winegard-marietta-college-professor-says-school/|title=Professor with controversial race theories says college won't hire him back|first=Christopher|last=Vondracek|accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref> or heretical ideas.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theamericanconservative.com/dreher/hounding-heretic-bo-winegard/|title=Hounding The Heretic Bo Winegard|first=Rod|last=Dreher|accessdate=7 March 2020}}</ref> The notion that human populations could have evolved different psychological tendencies is controversial because it suggests that all races may not have identical group averages on all socially valued traits. Other scholars, including Noah Carl, have been let go from their academic positions for defending this research,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://quillette.com/2019/05/28/noah-carl-an-update-on-the-young-scholar-fired-by-a-cambridge-college-for-thoughtcrime/|title=Noah Carl: An Update on the Young Scholar Fired by a Cambridge College for Thoughtcrime|first=Quillette|last=Magazine|accessdate=28 May 2019}}</ref> which critics describe as \u201cracist pseudoscience.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=https://medium.com/@racescienceopenletter/open-letter-no-to-racist-pseudoscience-at-cambridge-472e1a7c6dca|title=Open Letter: No to Racist Pseudoscience at Cambridge|accessdate=19 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Race and intelligence]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Winegard, Bo}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American social psychologists]]\n[[Category:Florida State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Marietta College faculty]]\n[[Category:People from Michigan]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=April 2020}}\n{{POV|date=April 2020}}\n{{Notability|Academics|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| honorific_prefix  = \n| name              = Bo Winegard\n| honorific_suffix  = \n| native_name       = \n| native_name_lang  = \n| image             = Bo Winegard2.jpg\n| image_size        = \n| image_upright     = \n| alt               = \n| caption           = \n| birth_name        = <!-- if different from \"name\" -->\n| birth_date        = {{birth date and age|1980|01|07}}\n| birth_place       = [[Greenville]], [[Michigan (state)|Michigan]]\n| death_date        = <!--{{death date and age |YYYY|MM|DD |YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date)-->\n| death_place       = \n| death_cause       = \n| resting_place     = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!--{{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}-->\n| other_names       = \n| pronounce         =\n| residence         = \n| citizenship       = \n| nationality       = American\n| fields            = [[Social psychology]]\n| workplaces        = [[Marietta College]]\n| patrons           = \n| education         = \n| alma_mater        = [[Florida State University]]\n| thesis_title      = \n| thesis_url        = \n| thesis_year       = \n| doctoral_advisor  = [[Roy Baumeister]]\n| academic_advisors = \n| doctoral_students = \n| notable_students  = \n| known_for         =\n| influences        = \n| influenced        = \n| awards            = \n| author_abbrev_bot = \n| author_abbrev_zoo = \n| spouse            = <!--(or | spouses = )-->\n| partner           = <!--(or | partners = )-->\n| children          = \n| signature         = <!--(filename only)-->\n| signature_alt     = \n| website           = <!--{{URL|www.example.com}}-->\n| footnotes         = \n}}\n'''Bo Winegard''' (born January 7, 1980) is an American social scientist and contributing writer at popular press outlets such as ''[[Quillette]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://quillette.com/author/bo-winegard/}}</ref> and ''[[Arc Digital]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://arcdigital.media/@winegabo}}</ref>.\n\n== Career ==\nBo Winegard received his Ph.D. in [[Social Psychology]] from [[Florida State University]] in 2018 under the supervision of Professor [[Roy Baumeister]]. In 2018, he became an Assistant Professor of Psychology at [[Marietta College]], but in 2020, his tenure-track position was terminated without official explanation.<<ref>{{cite web|url=https://quillette.com/2020/03/06/ive-been-fired-if-you-value-academic-freedom-that-should-worry-you/|title=I\u2019ve Been Fired. If You Value Academic Freedom, That Should Worry You|first=Bo|last=Winegard|accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Controversy==\n\nIn late 2019, Winegard was invited to give a talk at the [[University of Alabama]] on \u201cThe Evolution of Human Diversity\u201d.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://as.ua.edu/alumni/event/allele-the-evolution-of-human-diversity-dr-bo-winegard-marietta-college/|title=ALLELE: \"The Evolution of Human Diversity,\" Dr. Bo Winegard (Marietta College)}}</ref> The talk, which addressed the possibility that human populations may have evolved different psychological tendencies, stirred a controversy at the University because of the perceived \u201cracist implications\u201d of the research.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cw.ua.edu/56341/news/evolution-working-group-on-hosting-bo-winegard-it-was-our-mistake/|title=Evolution Working Group on hosting Bo Winegard: \u2018It was our mistake\u2019|first=Jeffrey|last=Kelly|accessdate=7 November 2019}}</ref>{{rs|date=April 2020}} In early 2020, Winegard was fired from his position at [[Marietta College]].\n\nChristopher Ferguson of ''[[Areo (magazine)|Areo]]'' contended that the talk explicitly denounced racism and urged people to treat others as individuals, not tokens of some group or another.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://areomagazine.com/2020/03/16/the-firing-of-bo-winegard-when-academic-freedom-and-outrage-collide/|title=The Firing of Bo Winegard: When Academic Freedom and Outrage Collide|first=Christopher|last=Ferguson|accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref> Some sources suggested that Winegard may have been fired for his \u201crisky research,\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2020/03/12/assistant-professor-says-hes-been-fired-because-he-dared-talk-about-human-population|title=Risky Research|first=Colleen|last=Flaherty|accessdate=12 March 2020}}</ref> \u201cwrongthink,\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thepostmillennial.com/professor-was-fired-from-his-tenure-track-job-for-wrongthink|title=Professor fired from his tenure track job for wrongthink|first=Libby|last=Emmons|accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref>{{rs|certain=y|date=April 2020}} \u201ccontroversial race theories,\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2020/mar/13/bo-winegard-marietta-college-professor-says-school/|title=Professor with controversial race theories says college won't hire him back|first=Christopher|last=Vondracek|accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref> or heretical ideas.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theamericanconservative.com/dreher/hounding-heretic-bo-winegard/|title=Hounding The Heretic Bo Winegard|first=Rod|last=Dreher|accessdate=7 March 2020}}</ref> The notion that human populations could have evolved different psychological tendencies is controversial because it suggests that all races may not have identical group averages on all socially valued traits. Other scholars, including Noah Carl, have been let go from their academic positions for defending this research,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://quillette.com/2019/05/28/noah-carl-an-update-on-the-young-scholar-fired-by-a-cambridge-college-for-thoughtcrime/|title=Noah Carl: An Update on the Young Scholar Fired by a Cambridge College for Thoughtcrime|first=Quillette|last=Magazine|accessdate=28 May 2019}}</ref> which critics describe as \u201cracist pseudoscience.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=https://medium.com/@racescienceopenletter/open-letter-no-to-racist-pseudoscience-at-cambridge-472e1a7c6dca|title=Open Letter: No to Racist Pseudoscience at Cambridge|accessdate=19 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Race and intelligence]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Winegard, Bo}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American social psychologists]]\n[[Category:Florida State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Marietta College faculty]]\n[[Category:People from Michigan]]\n", "name_user": "Hciam", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bo_Winegard"}
{"title_page": "Knap Hill", "text_new": "{{short description|Earthwork in Wiltshire, England}}\n{{Infobox Historic Site\n| name = Knap Hill\n| native_name =\n| image =Knap Hill - geograph.org.uk - 282649.jpg\n| caption =\n| locmapin = Wiltshire\n| map_caption =\n| coordinates = {{coord|51.37178|-1.82684|display=inline,title}}\n| location = England\n| area =\n| built =\n| architect =\n| architecture =[[Architecture of England#Pre-Roman architecture|British pre-Roman Architecture]]\n| governing_body =\n| designation1 =\n| designation1_offname =\n| designation1_date =\n| designation1_number =\n}}\n'''Knap Hill''' is an Neolithic [[causewayed enclosure]] near [[Alton Priors]] in northern [[Wiltshire]], England. It lies on the northern rim of the Vale of Pewsey, and is near two other Neolithic sites: [[Adam's Grave]], a chambered [[long barrow]] less than a mile to the west, and [[Rybury]], another causewayed enclosure, two miles beyond Adam's Grave.  The hilltop contains a smaller banked enclosure next to the Neolithic site, which appears to have been occupied from just before the arrival of the Romans until Saxon times.  This second enclosure was also briefly occupied during the 17th century, perhaps by shepherds.  Two barrows lay within the Neolithic enclosure, and at least one more outside it.  A Saxon sword was found in the smaller enclosure, and there is evidence of an intense fire in the same area, which may imply a violent end to the Romano-British occupation of the hilltop.\n\nThe site is notable for having been the first causewayed enclosure to be excavated and identified.  Benjamin and Maud Cunnington spent two summers investigating the site, in 1908 and 1909, and Maud Cunnington published two reports of their work, noting that there were multiple gaps in the ditch and bank surrounding the enclosure.  In the late 1920s, after the excavation of [[Windmill Hill]] among other sites, it became apparent that causewayed enclosures were a characteristic monument of the neolithic period.  Originally they were thought to have been inhabited, and so were called \"causewayed camps\", but that name has fallen out of use.  About seventy causewayed enclosures have now been found in Britain, and about a thousand in all in Europe.\n\nThe site was excavated again in 1961 by Graham Connah, who found a later burial in one of the ditches.  Connah kept excellent stratigraphic documentation of his finds, and this was taken advantage of by the Gathering Time project, which in 2011 published an analysis of radiocarbon dates from almost forty British causewayed enclosures.  The conclusion was that there was a 91% chance that Knap Hill was constructed between 3530 and 3375 BC, and a 92% chance that the ditch was filled by between 3525 and 3220 BC.\n\n== Background ==\n[[File:Knap Hill area from OS map 1961.png|thumb|upright=3|Area around Knap Hill in Wiltshire]]\nThe main archaeological site at Knap Hill is a [[causewayed enclosure]],<ref>Oswald et al. (2001), pp. 156\u2013157.</ref> a form of earthwork which began to appear in England in the early [[Neolithic British Isles|Neolithic]], from about 3700 BC.<ref>Oswald et al. (2001), p. 3.</ref>  They are characterized by a full or partial enclosure of an area with segmented ditches, often with earthworks and palisades in some combination.<ref name=\":3\" />  The use to which these enclosures has long been a matter of debate.  They may have seen use as settlements, with early investigators suggesting that the inhabitants lived in the ditches, though this idea was later abandoned in favour of any settlement being within the enclosure boundaries.<ref name=\":7\">Whittle, Healy & Bayliss (2015), p. 5.</ref>  In the report on the excavation at Knap Hill it was assumed that the ramparts were a form of defence.<ref name=\":6\">Cunnington (1912), p.48.</ref> The causeways were difficult to explain in military terms, though it was suggested they could have been sally ports for defenders to emerge from and attack a besieging force;<ref name=\":6\" /><ref>Curwen (1930), p. 50.</ref> evidence of attacks at some sites provided support for the idea that the enclosures were fortified settlements.<ref name=\":7\" /> They may have been seasonal meeting places, used for trading cattle or other goods such as pottery, and if they were a focus for the local people, they may have been evidence of a local hierarchy with a tribal chief.  There is also evidence that they played a role in funeral rites: material such as food, pottery, and human remains were deliberately deposited in the ditches.<ref>Whittle, Healy & Bayliss (2015), pp. 10\u201311.</ref>  They were constructed in a short time, which implies significant organization since the land may have had to be cleared which would have required substantial labour.<ref>Andersen (2019), p. 807.</ref>\n\nIn 1930, Cecil Curwen identified sixteen sites that were definitely or probably Neolithic causewayed enclosures.<ref>Curwen (1930).</ref><ref name=\":8\">Oswald et al. (2001), p. 25.</ref> Excavations at five of these had already confirmed them as Neolithic, and another four of Curwen's sites are now agreed to be Neolithic. <ref name=\":8\" />  A few more were found over the succeeding decades,<ref name=\":9\">Oswald et al. (2001), p. 31.</ref> and the list of known sites was significantly expanded with the use of aerial photography in the 1960s and early 1970s.<ref name=\":9\" /><ref>Mercer (1990), pp. 10\u201312.</ref>  The earlier sites were mostly found on chalk uplands, but many of the ones discovered from the air were on lower-lying ground.<ref name=\":9\" />  Over seventy are known in the British Isles,<ref name=\":7\" /> and they are one of the most common types of early Neolithic site from western Europe, with about a thousand known in all.<ref>Andersen (2019), p. 796.</ref>  They were built in the early Neolithic, which began at different times in different parts of Europe: the dates range from before 4000 BC in northern France, to shortly before 3000 BC in northern Germany, Denmark and Poland.<ref name=\":3\" />  The enclosures in southern Britain and Ireland began to appear not long before 3700 BC, and continued to be built for at least 200 years.  In a few cases enclosures that had already been built continued to be used as late as 3300 to 3200 BC.<ref>Whittle, Healy & Bayliss (2015), pp. 1\u20132.</ref>\n\n== Site ==\nKnap Hill is in Wiltshire, about a mile north of the village of [[Alton Priors]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://maps.nls.uk/view/95749848|title=View: SU16 (includes: Marlborough) \u2013 Ordnance Survey 1:25,000 maps of Great Britain, 1937\u20131961|website=maps.nls.uk|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>  It is part of the chalk hills that form the northern rim of the [[Vale of Pewsey]], and is flanked by Golden Ball Hill to the east, and Walker Hill to the west.<ref name=\":4\" />  Golden Ball Hill has traces of Mesolithic activity,<ref>Whittle, Bayliss & Healy (2015), p. 97.</ref> and two other Neolithic sites are nearby: [[Adam's Grave]], a chambered long barrow on Walker Hill, and [[Rybury]], a causewayed enclosure, two miles further west.<ref name=\":4\" />  The south side of the hill is the steepest, with more gradual slopes to the north and west.  There is a narrow neck of land that connects it to Golden Ball Hill to the east.<ref>Cunnington (1912), p. 42.</ref>  The hilltop at one time bore two round barrows inside the enclosure.<ref name=\":10\" /> One of these was destroyed in the 19th century by flint diggers.<ref name=\":10\" /><ref name=\":11\" />  A third barrow lies just outside the causewayed enclosure, to the southwest, and a fourth barrow may also have existed to the south, though the records that refer to it may be a confused reference to the third barrow.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.pastscape.org.uk/hob.aspx?hob_id=1301651|title=Pastscape \u2013 Detailed Result: ALTON 13|website=www.pastscape.org.uk|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.pastscape.org.uk/hob.aspx?hob_id=1301639|title=Pastscape \u2013 Detailed Result: ALTON 10|website=www.pastscape.org.uk|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">Connah (1965), p.22, note 7.</ref>\n\nThe Neolithic causewayed enclosure at the top of Knap Hill has a ditch, and a bank that runs inside it, that run along the northwestern edge of the hilltop, and extend partway down the southwestern and northeastern sides, with some of the bank extending past the ditch at the northeastern edge.<ref>Cunnington (1912), pp. 43\u201345.</ref>  Both the ditch and bank were built in seven segments, with six gaps, or causeways, between them.  Another short section of ditch at the eastern corner of the hill was divided into two sections.<ref>Cunnington (1912), p. 47.</ref>  To the northeast of the enclosure lies a smaller archaeological site known as the plateau enclosure,<ref name=\":12\" /> which dates from before and during the Romano-British occupation.<ref name=\":13\">Cunnington (1912), pp. 57\u201358.</ref>  The plateau enclosure was also occupied in the 1600s, perhaps by shepherds.<ref name=\":13\" />\n\nA bank, with a ditch on either side, runs from the southeastern corner of the causewayed enclosure down the hill, which is too steep for this to have been a pathway.<ref>Cunnington (1912), pp. 45\u201346.</ref><ref name=\":16\">Connah (1965), p. 2.</ref>  Similarly, from the fourth causeway (counting clockwise from the left on the Cunnington's plan, below), a bank runs down the hill, this time with only one parallel ditch.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":16\" /><ref name=\":17\">Connah (1965), pp. 9\u201310.</ref>  Both were probably boundary ditches.<ref name=\":16\" /><ref name=\":17\" />\n\n== Antiquarian and archaeological investigations ==\nKnap Hill was first mentioned as being of antiquarian interest in 1680, by [[John Aubrey]], who described it as \"a small Roman camp above Alton\".<ref>Mercer (1990), p. 20.</ref>  [[Sir Richard Hoare, 2nd Baronet|Richard Colt Hoare]] mentions Knap Hill early in the 19th century,{{#tag:ref|Hoare included Knap Hill in his two-volume compendium of  Wiltshire antiquities, ''Ancient History of North and South Wiltshire'' and ''History of Ancient Wiltshire'', published between 1812 and 1821.<ref>Murray (2007), p. 66.</ref>|group=notes}} noting \"two small barrows, and another on the outside\".<ref>Quoted in Thurnam (1860), p. 326.</ref>\n\n=== John Thurman, 1850s ===\n[[John Thurnam]] investigated the barrows between 1853 and 1857, but found the easternmost of the two barrows within the enclosure had been destroyed by that time by flint diggers, with no trace left.  The western barrow was about two feet high, with a small ditch around it.  Near the top of the barrow Thurman found animal bones, which he described as \"of a sheep and perhaps other ruminants\", and commented in his account that this was consistent with other barrows in Wiltshire, which often contained animal bones near the surface of the barrow.  He speculated that they were probably from a sacrifice or feast over the graves.  Under the middle of the barrow was a circular hole dug into the chalk, two feet deep and two feet across.  It was almost full of ashes and burnt bones. The barrow outside the enclosure, which lay to the southwest, was about a foot high and Thurnam found nothing there but some animal bones near the surface.<ref name=\":11\">Thurnam (1860), pp. 326\u2013327.</ref><ref name=\":10\">Cunnington (1912), p. 43.</ref>\n\n=== Benjamin and Maud Cunnington, 1908-9 ===\nThe Neolithic enclosure was first excavated by [[Maud Cunnington|Maud]] and [[Ben Cunnington (archaeologist)|Benjamin Cunnington]], in the summers of 1908 and 1909.  ODB 12.  The first summer's investigation revealed the segmented nature of the earthworks, and led to the publication of a short note by Maud Cunnington in the journal ''[[Man (journal)|Man]]'' in 1909 in which she asked readers of the journal to suggest explanations:<ref>Cunnington (1909), pp. 49\u201352.</ref>\n\n<blockquote>Recent excavations [at] Knap Hill Camp in Wiltshire revealed a feature which, if intentional, appears to be a method of defence hitherto unobserved in prehistoric fortifications in Britain...There are six openings or gaps through the rampart.  It was thought at first that...some of these gaps were due to cattle tracks, or possibly had been made for agricultural purposes....  Excavations clearly showed that none of these gaps in the rampart are the result of wear or of any accidental circumstance, but that they are actually part of the original construction of the camp....  Outside of, and corresponding to, each gap the ditch was never dug; that is to say, a solid gangway or causeway of unexcavated ground has been left in each case....Given the need for an entrenchment at all, it seems at first sight inexplicable why these frequent openings should have been left, when apparently they so weaken the whole construction....  It has been suggested...that the work of fortifications was never finished, [but there is] considerable evidence in favour of these causeways being an intentional feature of the original design of the camp... The possible use which the gangways may have served is put forward with all diffidence, and any suggestion on the subject would be welcomed.</blockquote>[[File:Knap Hill Camp map M.E. Cunnington 1911.png|thumb|upright=4|Map of Knap Hill showing the Cunningtons' excavations of 1908 and 1909]]\n\nThis was the first time that causewayed ditches had been identified,<ref name=\":4\">Connah (1965), p. 1.</ref> though earlier excavations had taken place at sites now known to be causewayed enclosures.<ref name=\":3\">Andersen (2019), p. 795.</ref>{{#tag:ref|For example, [[Peu-Richard culture|Peu-Richard]], in western France, was excavated in 1882 by [[Eug\u00e8ne Eschass\u00e9riaux|Baron Eschass\u00e9riaux]].<ref name=\":3\" />|group=notes}}  By the time the second summer's work had been completed, every causeway had been excavated sufficiently to prove that the ditches ended where the above-ground evidence indicated.<ref>Cunnington (1912), p. 59.</ref>\n\nThe discovery of a second enclosure, to the northeast of the original target of their excavation, complicated the Cunningtons' work.<ref name=\":10\" />  They labelled the new enclosure the \"Plateau Enclosure\" to distinguish it from the \"Old Camp\".<ref name=\":10\" /><ref name=\":12\">Cunnington (1912), p. 49.</ref>  In the old enclosure, they cleared a 54 foot long stretch of the second ditch (counting clockwise from the left), and discovered that the width and depth varied greatly, from seven feet deep and ten feet wide at the west end of the section, to eight feet deep and only eighteen inches wide at the east end.  They also made cuttings along the southern edge of the hilltop to determine if a ditch existed there which was no longer visible on the surface, and found two short ditch sections at the eastern corner (marked S\u2013S on the plan).<ref>Cunnington (1912), pp. 59\u201360.</ref>  Most of the relics obtained from the ditches of the old enclosure were found in clusters, and were usually within a foot of the bottom; they included some sherds of pottery, flint flakes and burnt flints, fragments of animal bones, and pieces of sarsen stone.  The only human bone found was a small jaw bone with worn teeth.<ref>Cunnington (1912), pp. 60\u201361.</ref>  The pottery was coarse, with flint inclusions, and was found associated with flint flakes, leading Maud Cunnington to suggest that the people who used the pottery may have been Neolithic, though she concluded that the inability to tell undecorated pottery of the [[Bronze Age]] and Neolithic periods apart meant that it was not possible to confidently assign a period.<ref name=\":15\">Cunnington (1912), p. 50.</ref><ref name=\":14\">Cunnington (1912), pp. 56\u201357.</ref>  The Cunningtons found several [[flint-knapping]] clusters, including one group of seventy-two flint chips six foot deep in the ditch.<ref>Cunnington (1912), pp. 61-62.</ref><ref name=\":18\">Whittle, Bayliss & Healy (2015), pp. 97-98.</ref>\n\nIt was clear to Cunnington that the plateau enclosure was much more recent than the old enclosure, since the plateau enclosure's southwestern ditch was dug through the old enclosure's ditch, which had silted up almost completely by that time.  Cunnington considered the plateau enclosure to be no earlier than the early [[Iron Age]].<ref name=\":12\" /><ref name=\":14\" />  The ditch and low rampart that surrounded the enclosure were mostly undetectable on the surface; Cunnington cut sections around the perimeter at intervals to confirm their path.<ref name=\":12\" />  A gap was also found in the plateau enclosure ditch at the southwestern edge, where it overlapped with the old enclosure, but Cunnington could not tell what the gap was for\u2014an entrance was implausible as the bank was very steep at that point.<ref name=\":15\" />  The pottery found in the plateau ditch and bank was of much better quality than the coarse Neolithic pottery associated with the old enclosure: it included [[bead-rim pottery]] which Cunnington dated to just before, or during the early years of, the Roman occupation.<ref>Cunnington (1912), pp. 50\u201351.</ref>\n[[File:Knap Hill Saxon sword.png|left|thumb|upright=2|Saxon sword found in the plateau enclosure by the Cunningtons]]\nWithin the plateau enclosure was a long bank, running from southwest to northeast, with a circular mound at the northeastern end.  Cunnington found pottery sherds in the long bank that she dated to Roman times, and also found in the centre of the bank that two pits lay beneath it, marked P.P. on the plan.  These had been dug from the ground level before the bank was raised, and were both circular, about 2 feet deep, and 3 1/2 to 4 feet in diameter.  These contained flint flakes, coarse pottery and some animal bones, and Cunnington concluded that they were contemporary with the old enclosure and that it was a coincidence the long bank was raised over them.<ref>Cunnington (1912), pp. 51\u201353.</ref>  A 6th-century [[Saxons|Saxon]] iron sword was found towards the edge of the long mound. A round fire hole was found under the circular mound, containing wood ash and pottery, some of which Cunnington identified as Roman.  Another fireplace was found to the southeast of the long mound, in a rectangular area of raised earth (which Cunnington referred to as the dais) ; this fireplace was T-shaped, and contained the lower stone of a quern, damaged by heat, four iron nails, and several fragments of pottery.  Cunnington suggested that the fireplace must have been unusable once the quern was in it, and that this, along with the presence of the sword and the evidence of intense heat, implied a catastrophic end to the inhabitation of the enclosure.<ref>Cunnington (1912), pp. 52\u201354.</ref>\n\nBetween the long bank and the dais were the remains of a small building (marked E on the plan), 23 feet by 13 1/2 feet, with walls made of blocks of chalk.  Postholes were found at intervals in the walls. A rubbish pile next to the building yielded a sherd of 17th century pottery, and in the area of the building and the dais were numerous clay pipes, some of which retained their makers' stamps and so could be dated with accuracy.  The pipes and the pottery sherds from this area both were dated to the 17th century, mixed with Roman pottery in the dais, which led Cunnington to conclude that the dais had been cultivated by the 17th-century inhabitants of the hilltop, since that would have led to turning the soil on the dais and mixing the relics at different levels.  The ruins of another rectangular building (F on the plan) was found against the eastern side of the plateau enclosure's bank, with both Roman and 17th-century pottery sherds in the wals and under the foundations.  It was apparent that the building had been erected after the plateau enclosure had been built, but Cunnington found no other evidence that would help determine its date.<ref>Cunnington (1912), pp. 55\u201356.</ref>\n\nThe Cunningtons also opened the barrow outside the old enclosure, to the southwest (not marked on their plan, but labelled \"Grinsell 10\" on Connah's plan, below), and found a skeleton fairly near the surface, face down.  It was missing all the bones of the legs and feet, and the right hand; Cunnington speculated that the skeleton had been placed so near the surface of the barrow that the missing bones had been disturbed by animals.  The only pottery sherds found were from the Roman period and were all near the surface, implying that the burial preceded the Roman occupation.<ref>Cunnington (1912), pp. 58\u201359.</ref>\n\nTwo low banks were found, running down the hill: one from the two ditches marked S on the plan, and one on the other side of the enclosure, leading down from the fourth causeway, counting clockwise from the left of the plan.  The one to the east was known locally as \"The Devil's Trackway\".  The western bank led for fifty yards towards an old track across the hill.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n=== C.W. Phillips, 1939 ===\nIn 1939 C.W. Phillips excavated a [[bowl barrow]] outside the enclosure, but never published a report.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" />  Two barrows outside the enclosure are listed in a gazetteer of Wiltshire by [[Leslie Grinsell]], published in 1957, identified as Alton 10 and Alton 13.  Phillips excavated Alton 13, but it may be that the two barrows are the same, in which case the barrow Phillips excavated was the same one that Thurman investigated in the 1850s.  Phillips found a crouched burial, at the old ground surface, and Neolithic potsherds; the potsherds may not indicate that the barrow is of Neolithic date since the sherds would have been present on the site at the time the barrow was constructed.  Grinsell cites Phillips to say that the barrow lay to the south of the causewayed enclosure, and if this is correct it is not the same barrow that Thurman opened.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Graham Connah, 1961 ===\n[[File:Knap Hill map RHCM Connah 1961.png|thumb|upright=4|Knap Hill site, showing trenches from the 1961 excavation]]\nIn 1961, the causewayed enclosure was excavated again, by [[Graham Connah]].<ref name=\":4\" />  Three trenches (i to iii in the diagram at right) were cut across three different segments of the ditches and banks, and one causeway (iv in the diagram) was fully excavated, including both ends of the two ditches abutting it.<ref>Connah (1965), pp. 2\u20133.</ref>  Like Cunnington, Connah found a knapping cluster at the surface of the chalk in one of his cuttings.<ref name=\":18\" />  Connah found only a few sherds of pottery, and so combined his finds with those from the earlier excavation for analysis purposes, though some documentation on the exact provenance of the earlier finds had been lost since 1912.  Most of the sherds found in 1961 had flint [[Temper (pottery)|inclusions]], but four sherds, from a single pot, had shell inclusions, and so must have come from at least 20 miles away.  Similar combinations of finds had been reported at [[Windmill Hill, Avebury|Windmill Hill]], [[Robin Hood's Ball]], and [[White Sheet Hill|Whitesheet Hill]].<ref name=\":5\">Connah (1965), p. 11.</ref>  Connah classified the pottery from the ditches as [[Windmill Hill ware]],<ref name=\":5\" /> a classification current in the 1960s that attempted to identify individual cultures within the Neolithic, but since overturned in favour of separating Neolithic sites into Early and Late Neolithic.<ref>Pouncett (2008), p. 37.</ref>  In addition to the Windmill Hill ware, fragments from seven or eight pots of [[Beaker ware]] were found.  Connah also found some Romano-British pottery in his cuttings, including four [[Samian ware|Samian]] sherds, one of which could be dated to the late 1st century AD.  Some later medieval pottery fragments could not be accurately dated.<ref>Connah (1965), p. 12.</ref><ref>Connah (1965), p. 14.</ref>\n\nIn one of the cuttings a skeleton of a woman was found, near the top of the ditch.  Nails found around the feet were interpreted as the remains of boots that had been reinforced with them.  Connah concluded that the skeleton probably dated to the Roman-British occupation, and that the Neolithic ditch was simply an area of conveniently soft ground for the burial.<ref>Connah (1965), p. 7.</ref>  The woman was probably in her 40s when she died, and was about 5 feet 2 inches tall.  She suffered from osteo-arthritis, and had abcesses in her jaw: an evaluation by the Duckworth Laboratory in Cambridge concluded that she \"most probably suffered agonies\".<ref>Connah (1965). pp. 18\u201319.</ref>\n\nConnah identified ditches on both sides of the bank leading down from the eastern corner of the causewayed enclosure, and his excavation of the fourth causeway found a shallow ditch cut in the chalk along the line of the bank leading down the hill on that side, which lay beneath a ditch along one side of that bank.  Neither ditch was noticed by the Cunningtons.  Connah concluded that both were likely to have been constructed to mark boundaries.<ref name=\":16\" /><ref name=\":17\" />\n\n=== Gathering Time, 2011 ===\nIn 2011, the Gathering Time project published the results of a programme to reanalyze the radiocarbon dates of nearly 40 causewayed enclosures, using [[Bayesian inference|Bayesian analysis]].  Knap Hill was one of the sites included in the project.  Connah had obtained two radiocarbon dates on samples gathered during the 1961 excavation, which he had published in 1969; these results were included in the Gathering Time analysis, and one was resampled and tested again.  Five other samples drawn from Connah's finds were also radiocarbon dated, as Connah's stratigraphic recording was precise enough to make it possible to identify samples which had good association with the building of the enclosure.  The conclusion was that there was a 91% chance that Knap Hill was constructed between 3530 and 3375 BC, and a 92% chance that the ditch was filled by between 3525 and 3220 BC.<ref>Whittle, Bayliss & Healy (2015), pp. 99-102.</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n<references group=notes/>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== Sources ==\n\n*{{Cite book|last=Andersen|first=Niels H.|title=The Oxford Handbook of Neolithic Europe|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2019|isbn=978-0-19-883249-2|editor-last=Fowler|editor-first=Chris|location=Oxford|pages=795-812|chapter=Causewayed Enclosures in Northern and Western Europe|orig-year=2015|editor-last2=Harding|editor-first2=Jan|editor-last3=Hofmann|editor-first3=Daniela}}\n*{{Cite journal|last=Connah|first=Graham|date=1969|title=Radiocarbon dating for Knap Hill|journal=Antiquity|volume=43|pages=304-305|via=|issue=172|url=|ref=none}}\n*{{Cite journal|last=Connah|first=Graham|last2=Smith|first2=I.F.|date=1965|title=Excavations at Knap Hill, Alton Priors|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/138882#page/7/mode/1up|journal=Wiltshire Archaeological and Natural History Magazine|volume=60|pages=1\u201323|via=}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Crawford|first=O.G.S.|title=Archaeology in the Field|publisher=Phoenix House|year=1960|location=London|pages=|orig-year=1953}}\n*{{Cite journal|last=Cunnington|first=M.E.|year=1909|title=On a remarkable feature in the entrenchments of Knap Hill Camp, Wiltshire|url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/2839810|journal=Man|volume=9|pages=49\u201352|doi=10.2307/2839810}}\n* {{Cite journal|last=Cunnington|first=M.E.|date=1912|title=Knap Hill Camp|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/132441#page/68/mode/1up|journal=Wiltshire Archaeological and Natural History Magazine|volume=37|pages=42-65|via=}}\n*{{Cite journal|last=Curwen|first=E. Cecil|date=1930|title=Neolithic camps|journal=Antiquity|volume=4|pages=22\u201354|via=|issue=13}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Mercer|first=R.J.|title=Causewayed Enclosures|publisher=Shire Archaeology|year=1990|isbn=0-7478-0064-2|location=Princes Risborough, UK|pages=}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Murray|first=Tim|title=Milestones in Archaeology: A Chronological Encyclopedia|publisher=ABC-CLIO|year=2007|isbn=978-1-57607-186-1|location=Santa Barbara, California|pages=}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Oswald|first=Alastair|title=The Creation of Monuments: Neolithic Causewayed Enclosures in the British Isles|last2=Dyer|first2=Carolyn|last3=Barber|first3=Martin|publisher=English Heritage|year=2001|isbn=1-873592-42-6|location=Swindon, UK|pages=}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Pouncett|first=John|title=The Handbook of British Archaeology|publisher=Constable|year=2008|isbn=978-1-84529-606-3|editor-last=Adkins|editor-first=Roy|location=London|pages=36-62|chapter=The Neolithic Period|editor-last2=Adkins|editor-first2=Lesley|editor-last3=Leitch|editor-first3=Victoria}}\n* {{Cite journal|last=Thurnam|first=John|date=1860|title=Examination of Barrows on the Downs of North Wiltshire|url=https://archive.org/details/wiltshirearchaeo06wilt/page/316/mode/2up|journal=Wiltshire Archaeological and Natural History Magazine|volume=6|pages=317\u2013336|via=}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Whittle|first=Alasdair|title=Gathering Time: Dating the Early Neolithic Enclosures of Southern Britain and Ireland|publisher=Oxbow|year=2015|isbn=978-1-84217-425-8|editor-last=Whittle|editor-first=Alasdair|location=Oxford|pages=60-110|chapter=The North Wiltshire Downs|editor-last2=Healy|editor-first2=Frances|editor-last3=Bayliss|editor-first3=Alex|orig-year=2011|last2=Bayliss|first2=Alex|last3=Healy|first3=Frances}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Whittle|first=Alasdair|title=Gathering Time: Dating the Early Neolithic Enclosures of Southern Britain and Ireland|publisher=Oxbow|year=2015|isbn=978-1-84217-425-8|editor-last=Whittle|editor-first=Alasdair|location=Oxford|pages=1-16|chapter=Gathering time: causewayed enclosures and the early Neolithic of southern Britain and Ireland|editor-last2=Healy|editor-first2=Frances|editor-last3=Bayliss|editor-first3=Alex|orig-year=2011|last2=Healy|first2=Frances|last3=Bayliss|first3=Alex}}\n\n[[Category:Stone Age sites in England]]\n[[Category:Archaeological sites in Wiltshire]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Wiltshire]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Wiltshire]]\n[[Category:Causewayed enclosures]]\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Knap Hill}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Earthwork in Wiltshire, England}}\n{{Infobox Historic Site\n| name = Knap Hill\n| native_name =\n| image =Knap Hill - geograph.org.uk - 282649.jpg\n| caption =\n| locmapin = Wiltshire\n| map_caption =\n| coordinates = {{coord|51.37178|-1.82684|display=inline,title}}\n| location = England\n| area =\n| built =\n| architect =\n| architecture =[[Architecture of England#Pre-Roman architecture|British pre-Roman Architecture]]\n| governing_body =\n| designation1 =\n| designation1_offname =\n| designation1_date =\n| designation1_number =\n}}\n'''Knap Hill''' is an Neolithic [[causewayed enclosure]] near [[Alton Priors]] in northern [[Wiltshire]], England. It lies on the northern rim of the Vale of Pewsey, and is near two other Neolithic sites: [[Adam's Grave]], a chambered [[long barrow]] less than a mile to the west, and [[Rybury]], another causewayed enclosure, two miles beyond Adam's Grave.  The hilltop contains a smaller banked enclosure next to the Neolithic site, which appears to have been occupied from just before the arrival of the Romans until Saxon times.  This second enclosure was also briefly occupied during the 17th century, perhaps by shepherds.  Two barrows lay within the Neolithic enclosure, and at least one more outside it.  A Saxon sword was found in the smaller enclosure, and there is evidence of an intense fire in the same area, which may imply a violent end to the Romano-British occupation of the hilltop.\n\nThe site is notable for having been the first causewayed enclosure to be excavated and identified.  Benjamin and Maud Cunnington spent two summers investigating the site, in 1908 and 1909, and Maud Cunnington published two reports of their work, noting that there were multiple gaps in the ditch and bank surrounding the enclosure.  In the late 1920s, after the excavation of Windmill Hill among other sites, it became apparent that causewayed enclosures were a characteristic monument of the neolithic period.  Originally they were thought to have been inhabited, and so were called \"causewayed camps\", but that name has fallen out of use.  About seventy causewayed enclosures have now been found in Britain, and about a thousand in all in Europe.\n\nThe site was excavated again in 1961 by Graham Connah, who found a later burial in one of the ditches.  Connah kept excellent stratigraphic documentation of his finds, and this was taken advantage of by the Gathering Time project, which in 2011 published an analysis of radiocarbon dates from almost forty British causewayed enclosures.  The conclusion was that there was a 91% chance that Knap Hill was constructed between 3530 and 3375 BC, and a 92% chance that the ditch was filled by between 3525 and 3220 BC.\n\n== Background ==\n[[File:Knap Hill area from OS map 1961.png|thumb|upright=3|Area around Knap Hill in Wiltshire]]\nThe main archaeological site at Knap Hill is a [[causewayed enclosure]],<ref>Oswald et al. (2001), pp. 156\u2013157.</ref> a form of earthwork which began to appear in England in the early [[Neolithic British Isles|Neolithic]], from about 3700 BC.<ref>Oswald et al. (2001), p. 3.</ref>  They are characterized by a full or partial enclosure of an area with segmented ditches, often with earthworks and palisades in some combination.<ref name=\":3\" />  The use to which these enclosures has long been a matter of debate.  They may have seen use as settlements, with early investigators suggesting that the inhabitants lived in the ditches, though this idea was later abandoned in favour of any settlement being within the enclosure boundaries.<ref name=\":7\">Whittle, Healy & Bayliss (2015), p. 5.</ref>  In the report on the excavation at Knap Hill it was assumed that the ramparts were a form of defence.<ref name=\":6\">Cunnington (1912), p.48.</ref> The causeways were difficult to explain in military terms, though it was suggested they could have been sally ports for defenders to emerge from and attack a besieging force;<ref name=\":6\" /><ref>Curwen (1930), p. 50.</ref> evidence of attacks at some sites provided support for the idea that the enclosures were fortified settlements.<ref name=\":7\" /> They may have been seasonal meeting places, used for trading cattle or other goods such as pottery, and if they were a focus for the local people, they may have been evidence of a local hierarchy with a tribal chief.  There is also evidence that they played a role in funeral rites: material such as food, pottery, and human remains were deliberately deposited in the ditches.<ref>Whittle, Healy & Bayliss (2015), pp. 10\u201311.</ref>  They were constructed in a short time, which implies significant organization since the land may have had to be cleared which would have required substantial labour.<ref>Andersen (2019), p. 807.</ref>\n\nIn 1930, Cecil Curwen identified sixteen sites that were definitely or probably Neolithic causewayed enclosures.<ref>Curwen (1930).</ref><ref name=\":8\">Oswald et al. (2001), p. 25.</ref> Excavations at five of these had already confirmed them as Neolithic, and another four of Curwen's sites are now agreed to be Neolithic. <ref name=\":8\" />  A few more were found over the succeeding decades,<ref name=\":9\">Oswald et al. (2001), p. 31.</ref> and the list of known sites was significantly expanded with the use of aerial photography in the 1960s and early 1970s.<ref name=\":9\" /><ref>Mercer (1990), pp. 10\u201312.</ref>  The earlier sites were mostly found on chalk uplands, but many of the ones discovered from the air were on lower-lying ground.<ref name=\":9\" />  Over seventy are known in the British Isles,<ref name=\":7\" /> and they are one of the most common types of early Neolithic site from western Europe, with about a thousand known in all.<ref>Andersen (2019), p. 796.</ref>  They were built in the early Neolithic, which began at different times in different parts of Europe: the dates range from before 4000 BC in northern France, to shortly before 3000 BC in northern Germany, Denmark and Poland.<ref name=\":3\" />  The enclosures in southern Britain and Ireland began to appear not long before 3700 BC, and continued to be built for at least 200 years.  In a few cases enclosures that had already been built continued to be used as late as 3300 to 3200 BC.<ref>Whittle, Healy & Bayliss (2015), pp. 1\u20132.</ref>\n\n== Site ==\nKnap Hill is in Wiltshire, about a mile north of the village of [[Alton Priors]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://maps.nls.uk/view/95749848|title=View: SU16 (includes: Marlborough) \u2013 Ordnance Survey 1:25,000 maps of Great Britain, 1937\u20131961|website=maps.nls.uk|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>  It is part of the chalk hills that form the northern rim of the [[Vale of Pewsey]], and is flanked by Golden Ball Hill to the east, and Walker Hill to the west.<ref name=\":4\" />  Golden Ball Hill has traces of Mesolithic activity,<ref>Whittle, Bayliss & Healy (2015), p. 97.</ref> and two other Neolithic sites are nearby: [[Adam's Grave]], a chambered long barrow on Walker Hill, and [[Rybury]], a causewayed enclosure, two miles further west.<ref name=\":4\" />  The south side of the hill is the steepest, with more gradual slopes to the north and west.  There is a narrow neck of land that connects it to Golden Ball Hill to the east.<ref>Cunnington (1912), p. 42.</ref>  The hilltop at one time bore two round barrows inside the enclosure.<ref name=\":10\" /> One of these was destroyed in the 19th century by flint diggers.<ref name=\":10\" /><ref name=\":11\" />  A third barrow lies just outside the causewayed enclosure, to the southwest, and a fourth barrow may also have existed to the south, though the records that refer to it may be a confused reference to the third barrow.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.pastscape.org.uk/hob.aspx?hob_id=1301651|title=Pastscape \u2013 Detailed Result: ALTON 13|website=www.pastscape.org.uk|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.pastscape.org.uk/hob.aspx?hob_id=1301639|title=Pastscape \u2013 Detailed Result: ALTON 10|website=www.pastscape.org.uk|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">Connah (1965), p.22, note 7.</ref>\n\nThe Neolithic causewayed enclosure at the top of Knap Hill has a ditch, and a bank that runs inside it, that run along the northwestern edge of the hilltop, and extend partway down the southwestern and northeastern sides, with some of the bank extending past the ditch at the northeastern edge.<ref>Cunnington (1912), pp. 43\u201345.</ref>  Both the ditch and bank were built in seven segments, with six gaps, or causeways, between them.  Another short section of ditch at the eastern corner of the hill was divided into two sections.<ref>Cunnington (1912), p. 47.</ref>  To the northeast of the enclosure lies a smaller archaeological site known as the plateau enclosure,<ref name=\":12\" /> which dates from before and during the Romano-British occupation.<ref name=\":13\">Cunnington (1912), pp. 57\u201358.</ref>  The plateau enclosure was also occupied in the 1600s, perhaps by shepherds.<ref name=\":13\" />\n\nA bank, with a ditch on either side, runs from the southeastern corner of the causewayed enclosure down the hill, which is too steep for this to have been a pathway.<ref>Cunnington (1912), pp. 45\u201346.</ref><ref name=\":16\">Connah (1965), p. 2.</ref>  Similarly, from the fourth causeway (counting clockwise from the left on the Cunnington's plan, below), a bank runs down the hill, this time with only one parallel ditch.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":16\" /><ref name=\":17\">Connah (1965), pp. 9\u201310.</ref>  Both were probably boundary ditches.<ref name=\":16\" /><ref name=\":17\" />\n\n== Antiquarian and archaeological investigations ==\nKnap Hill was first mentioned as being of antiquarian interest in 1680, by [[John Aubrey]], who described it as \"a small Roman camp above Alton\".<ref>Mercer (1990), p. 20.</ref>  [[Sir Richard Hoare, 2nd Baronet|Richard Colt Hoare]] mentions Knap Hill early in the 19th century,{{#tag:ref|Hoare included Knap Hill in his two-volume compendium of  Wiltshire antiquities, ''Ancient History of North and South Wiltshire'' and ''History of Ancient Wiltshire'', published between 1812 and 1821.<ref>Murray (2007), p. 66.</ref>|group=notes}} noting \"two small barrows, and another on the outside\".<ref>Quoted in Thurnam (1860), p. 326.</ref>\n\n=== John Thurman, 1850s ===\n[[John Thurnam]] investigated the barrows between 1853 and 1857, but found the easternmost of the two barrows within the enclosure had been destroyed by that time by flint diggers, with no trace left.  The western barrow was about two feet high, with a small ditch around it.  Near the top of the barrow Thurman found animal bones, which he described as \"of a sheep and perhaps other ruminants\", and commented in his account that this was consistent with other barrows in Wiltshire, which often contained animal bones near the surface of the barrow.  He speculated that they were probably from a sacrifice or feast over the graves.  Under the middle of the barrow was a circular hole dug into the chalk, two feet deep and two feet across.  It was almost full of ashes and burnt bones. The barrow outside the enclosure, which lay to the southwest, was about a foot high and Thurnam found nothing there but some animal bones near the surface.<ref name=\":11\">Thurnam (1860), pp. 326\u2013327.</ref><ref name=\":10\">Cunnington (1912), p. 43.</ref>\n\n=== Benjamin and Maud Cunnington, 1908-9 ===\nThe Neolithic enclosure was first excavated by [[Maud Cunnington|Maud]] and [[Ben Cunnington (archaeologist)|Benjamin Cunnington]], in the summers of 1908 and 1909.  ODB 12.  The first summer's investigation revealed the segmented nature of the earthworks, and led to the publication of a short note by Maud Cunnington in the journal ''[[Man (journal)|Man]]'' in 1909 in which she asked readers of the journal to suggest explanations:<ref>Cunnington (1909), pp. 49\u201352.</ref>\n\n<blockquote>Recent excavations [at] Knap Hill Camp in Wiltshire revealed a feature which, if intentional, appears to be a method of defence hitherto unobserved in prehistoric fortifications in Britain...There are six openings or gaps through the rampart.  It was thought at first that...some of these gaps were due to cattle tracks, or possibly had been made for agricultural purposes....  Excavations clearly showed that none of these gaps in the rampart are the result of wear or of any accidental circumstance, but that they are actually part of the original construction of the camp....  Outside of, and corresponding to, each gap the ditch was never dug; that is to say, a solid gangway or causeway of unexcavated ground has been left in each case....Given the need for an entrenchment at all, it seems at first sight inexplicable why these frequent openings should have been left, when apparently they so weaken the whole construction....  It has been suggested...that the work of fortifications was never finished, [but there is] considerable evidence in favour of these causeways being an intentional feature of the original design of the camp... The possible use which the gangways may have served is put forward with all diffidence, and any suggestion on the subject would be welcomed.</blockquote>[[File:Knap Hill Camp map M.E. Cunnington 1911.png|thumb|upright=4|Map of Knap Hill showing the Cunningtons' excavations of 1908 and 1909]]\n\nThis was the first time that causewayed ditches had been identified,<ref name=\":4\">Connah (1965), p. 1.</ref> though earlier excavations had taken place at sites now known to be causewayed enclosures.<ref name=\":3\">Andersen (2019), p. 795.</ref>{{#tag:ref|For example, [[Peu-Richard culture|Peu-Richard]], in western France, was excavated in 1882 by [[Eug\u00e8ne Eschass\u00e9riaux|Baron Eschass\u00e9riaux]].<ref name=\":3\" />|group=notes}}  By the time the second summer's work had been completed, every causeway had been excavated sufficiently to prove that the ditches ended where the above-ground evidence indicated.<ref>Cunnington (1912), p. 59.</ref>\n\nThe discovery of a second enclosure, to the northeast of the original target of their excavation, complicated the Cunningtons' work.<ref name=\":10\" />  They labelled the new enclosure the \"Plateau Enclosure\" to distinguish it from the \"Old Camp\".<ref name=\":10\" /><ref name=\":12\">Cunnington (1912), p. 49.</ref>  In the old enclosure, they cleared a 54 foot long stretch of the second ditch (counting clockwise from the left), and discovered that the width and depth varied greatly, from seven feet deep and ten feet wide at the west end of the section, to eight feet deep and only eighteen inches wide at the east end.  They also made cuttings along the southern edge of the hilltop to determine if a ditch existed there which was no longer visible on the surface, and found two short ditch sections at the eastern corner (marked S\u2013S on the plan).<ref>Cunnington (1912), pp. 59\u201360.</ref>  Most of the relics obtained from the ditches of the old enclosure were found in clusters, and were usually within a foot of the bottom; they included some sherds of pottery, flint flakes and burnt flints, fragments of animal bones, and pieces of sarsen stone.  The only human bone found was a small jaw bone with worn teeth.<ref>Cunnington (1912), pp. 60\u201361.</ref>  The pottery was coarse, with flint inclusions, and was found associated with flint flakes, leading Maud Cunnington to suggest that the people who used the pottery may have been Neolithic, though she concluded that the inability to tell undecorated pottery of the [[Bronze Age]] and Neolithic periods apart meant that it was not possible to confidently assign a period.<ref name=\":15\">Cunnington (1912), p. 50.</ref><ref name=\":14\">Cunnington (1912), pp. 56\u201357.</ref>  The Cunningtons found several [[flint-knapping]] clusters, including one group of seventy-two flint chips six foot deep in the ditch.<ref>Cunnington (1912), pp. 61-62.</ref><ref name=\":18\">Whittle, Bayliss & Healy (2015), pp. 97-98.</ref>\n\nIt was clear to Cunnington that the plateau enclosure was much more recent than the old enclosure, since the plateau enclosure's southwestern ditch was dug through the old enclosure's ditch, which had silted up almost completely by that time.  Cunnington considered the plateau enclosure to be no earlier than the early [[Iron Age]].<ref name=\":12\" /><ref name=\":14\" />  The ditch and low rampart that surrounded the enclosure were mostly undetectable on the surface; Cunnington cut sections around the perimeter at intervals to confirm their path.<ref name=\":12\" />  A gap was also found in the plateau enclosure ditch at the southwestern edge, where it overlapped with the old enclosure, but Cunnington could not tell what the gap was for\u2014an entrance was implausible as the bank was very steep at that point.<ref name=\":15\" />  The pottery found in the plateau ditch and bank was of much better quality than the coarse Neolithic pottery associated with the old enclosure: it included [[bead-rim pottery]] which Cunnington dated to just before, or during the early years of, the Roman occupation.<ref>Cunnington (1912), pp. 50\u201351.</ref>\n[[File:Knap Hill Saxon sword.png|left|thumb|upright=2|Saxon sword found in the plateau enclosure by the Cunningtons]]\nWithin the plateau enclosure was a long bank, running from southwest to northeast, with a circular mound at the northeastern end.  Cunnington found pottery sherds in the long bank that she dated to Roman times, and also found in the centre of the bank that two pits lay beneath it, marked P.P. on the plan.  These had been dug from the ground level before the bank was raised, and were both circular, about 2 feet deep, and 3 1/2 to 4 feet in diameter.  These contained flint flakes, coarse pottery and some animal bones, and Cunnington concluded that they were contemporary with the old enclosure and that it was a coincidence the long bank was raised over them.<ref>Cunnington (1912), pp. 51\u201353.</ref>  A 6th-century [[Saxons|Saxon]] iron sword was found towards the edge of the long mound. A round fire hole was found under the circular mound, containing wood ash and pottery, some of which Cunnington identified as Roman.  Another fireplace was found to the southeast of the long mound, in a rectangular area of raised earth (which Cunnington referred to as the dais) ; this fireplace was T-shaped, and contained the lower stone of a quern, damaged by heat, four iron nails, and several fragments of pottery.  Cunnington suggested that the fireplace must have been unusable once the quern was in it, and that this, along with the presence of the sword and the evidence of intense heat, implied a catastrophic end to the inhabitation of the enclosure.<ref>Cunnington (1912), pp. 52\u201354.</ref>\n\nBetween the long bank and the dais were the remains of a small building (marked E on the plan), 23 feet by 13 1/2 feet, with walls made of blocks of chalk.  Postholes were found at intervals in the walls. A rubbish pile next to the building yielded a sherd of 17th century pottery, and in the area of the building and the dais were numerous clay pipes, some of which retained their makers' stamps and so could be dated with accuracy.  The pipes and the pottery sherds from this area both were dated to the 17th century, mixed with Roman pottery in the dais, which led Cunnington to conclude that the dais had been cultivated by the 17th-century inhabitants of the hilltop, since that would have led to turning the soil on the dais and mixing the relics at different levels.  The ruins of another rectangular building (F on the plan) was found against the eastern side of the plateau enclosure's bank, with both Roman and 17th-century pottery sherds in the wals and under the foundations.  It was apparent that the building had been erected after the plateau enclosure had been built, but Cunnington found no other evidence that would help determine its date.<ref>Cunnington (1912), pp. 55\u201356.</ref>\n\nThe Cunningtons also opened the barrow outside the old enclosure, to the southwest (not marked on their plan, but labelled \"Grinsell 10\" on Connah's plan, below), and found a skeleton fairly near the surface, face down.  It was missing all the bones of the legs and feet, and the right hand; Cunnington speculated that the skeleton had been placed so near the surface of the barrow that the missing bones had been disturbed by animals.  The only pottery sherds found were from the Roman period and were all near the surface, implying that the burial preceded the Roman occupation.<ref>Cunnington (1912), pp. 58\u201359.</ref>\n\nTwo low banks were found, running down the hill: one from the two ditches marked S on the plan, and one on the other side of the enclosure, leading down from the fourth causeway, counting clockwise from the left of the plan.  The one to the east was known locally as \"The Devil's Trackway\".  The western bank led for fifty yards towards an old track across the hill.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n=== C.W. Phillips, 1939 ===\nIn 1939 C.W. Phillips excavated a [[bowl barrow]] outside the enclosure, but never published a report.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" />  Two barrows outside the enclosure are listed in a gazetteer of Wiltshire by [[Leslie Grinsell]], published in 1957, identified as Alton 10 and Alton 13.  Phillips excavated Alton 13, but it may be that the two barrows are the same, in which case the barrow Phillips excavated was the same one that Thurman investigated in the 1850s.  Phillips found a crouched burial, at the old ground surface, and Neolithic potsherds; the potsherds may not indicate that the barrow is of Neolithic date since the sherds would have been present on the site at the time the barrow was constructed.  Grinsell cites Phillips to say that the barrow lay to the south of the causewayed enclosure, and if this is correct it is not the same barrow that Thurman opened.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Graham Connah, 1961 ===\n[[File:Knap Hill map RHCM Connah 1961.png|thumb|upright=4|Knap Hill site, showing trenches from the 1961 excavation]]\nIn 1961, the causewayed enclosure was excavated again, by [[Graham Connah]].<ref name=\":4\" />  Three trenches (i to iii in the diagram at right) were cut across three different segments of the ditches and banks, and one causeway (iv in the diagram) was fully excavated, including both ends of the two ditches abutting it.<ref>Connah (1965), pp. 2\u20133.</ref>  Like Cunnington, Connah found a knapping cluster at the surface of the chalk in one of his cuttings.<ref name=\":18\" />  Connah found only a few sherds of pottery, and so combined his finds with those from the earlier excavation for analysis purposes, though some documentation on the exact provenance of the earlier finds had been lost since 1912.  Most of the sherds found in 1961 had flint [[Temper (pottery)|inclusions]], but four sherds, from a single pot, had shell inclusions, and so must have come from at least 20 miles away.  Similar combinations of finds had been reported at [[Windmill Hill, Avebury|Windmill Hill]], [[Robin Hood's Ball]], and [[White Sheet Hill|Whitesheet Hill]].<ref name=\":5\">Connah (1965), p. 11.</ref>  Connah classified the pottery from the ditches as [[Windmill Hill ware]],<ref name=\":5\" /> a classification current in the 1960s that attempted to identify individual cultures within the Neolithic, but since overturned in favour of separating Neolithic sites into Early and Late Neolithic.<ref>Pouncett (2008), p. 37.</ref>  In addition to the Windmill Hill ware, fragments from seven or eight pots of [[Beaker ware]] were found.  Connah also found some Romano-British pottery in his cuttings, including four [[Samian ware|Samian]] sherds, one of which could be dated to the late 1st century AD.  Some later medieval pottery fragments could not be accurately dated.<ref>Connah (1965), p. 12.</ref><ref>Connah (1965), p. 14.</ref>\n\nIn one of the cuttings a skeleton of a woman was found, near the top of the ditch.  Nails found around the feet were interpreted as the remains of boots that had been reinforced with them.  Connah concluded that the skeleton probably dated to the Roman-British occupation, and that the Neolithic ditch was simply an area of conveniently soft ground for the burial.<ref>Connah (1965), p. 7.</ref>  The woman was probably in her 40s when she died, and was about 5 feet 2 inches tall.  She suffered from osteo-arthritis, and had abcesses in her jaw: an evaluation by the Duckworth Laboratory in Cambridge concluded that she \"most probably suffered agonies\".<ref>Connah (1965). pp. 18\u201319.</ref>\n\nConnah identified ditches on both sides of the bank leading down from the eastern corner of the causewayed enclosure, and his excavation of the fourth causeway found a shallow ditch cut in the chalk along the line of the bank leading down the hill on that side, which lay beneath a ditch along one side of that bank.  Neither ditch was noticed by the Cunningtons.  Connah concluded that both were likely to have been constructed to mark boundaries.<ref name=\":16\" /><ref name=\":17\" />\n\n=== Gathering Time, 2011 ===\nIn 2011, the Gathering Time project published the results of a programme to reanalyze the radiocarbon dates of nearly 40 causewayed enclosures, using [[Bayesian inference|Bayesian analysis]].  Knap Hill was one of the sites included in the project.  Connah had obtained two radiocarbon dates on samples gathered during the 1961 excavation, which he had published in 1969; these results were included in the Gathering Time analysis, and one was resampled and tested again.  Five other samples drawn from Connah's finds were also radiocarbon dated, as Connah's stratigraphic recording was precise enough to make it possible to identify samples which had good association with the building of the enclosure.  The conclusion was that there was a 91% chance that Knap Hill was constructed between 3530 and 3375 BC, and a 92% chance that the ditch was filled by between 3525 and 3220 BC.<ref>Whittle, Bayliss & Healy (2015), pp. 99-102.</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n<references group=notes/>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== Sources ==\n\n*{{Cite book|last=Andersen|first=Niels H.|title=The Oxford Handbook of Neolithic Europe|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2019|isbn=978-0-19-883249-2|editor-last=Fowler|editor-first=Chris|location=Oxford|pages=795-812|chapter=Causewayed Enclosures in Northern and Western Europe|orig-year=2015|editor-last2=Harding|editor-first2=Jan|editor-last3=Hofmann|editor-first3=Daniela}}\n*{{Cite journal|last=Connah|first=Graham|date=1969|title=Radiocarbon dating for Knap Hill|journal=Antiquity|volume=43|pages=304-305|via=|issue=172|url=|ref=none}}\n*{{Cite journal|last=Connah|first=Graham|last2=Smith|first2=I.F.|date=1965|title=Excavations at Knap Hill, Alton Priors|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/138882#page/7/mode/1up|journal=Wiltshire Archaeological and Natural History Magazine|volume=60|pages=1\u201323|via=}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Crawford|first=O.G.S.|title=Archaeology in the Field|publisher=Phoenix House|year=1960|location=London|pages=|orig-year=1953}}\n*{{Cite journal|last=Cunnington|first=M.E.|year=1909|title=On a remarkable feature in the entrenchments of Knap Hill Camp, Wiltshire|url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/2839810|journal=Man|volume=9|pages=49\u201352|doi=10.2307/2